# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: caroline-islands
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:caroline-islands/academia-antártica] The **Academia Antártica** ("Antarctic Academy") was a society of writers, poets and intellectuals—mostly of the criollo caste—that assembled in Lima, Peru, in the 16th and 17th centuries.
[src:caroline-islands/academia-antártica] Their objective was to author a body of literature that matched or surpassed that of Europe's and would prove that literariness indeed thrived in Spain's remotest colonies.
[src:caroline-islands/academia-antártica] These are dated 1608 and 1617, respectively.
[src:caroline-islands/academia-antártica] In the late 16th century, Lima, Peru, was a vibrant cultural center characterized by a widespread appreciation for literature.
[src:caroline-islands/academia-antártica] Even in "mills, mines and haciendas", not to mention in the homes of the aristocracy, classical Greek and Roman texts were circulated heavily.
[src:caroline-islands/academia-antártica] These included the writings of Aristotle, Herodotus, Petrarch, Cicero and Ovid.
[src:caroline-islands/academia-antártica] Indeed, one of the Academia's most distinguishing features is its members' imitations of—and relentless allusions to—classical canonical texts.
[src:caroline-islands/academia-antártica] The literary community in Lima was keenly attentive to cultural trends in Europe.
[src:caroline-islands/academia-antártica] It is likely that certain Limeño writers felt compelled to form the Academia Antártica in the last decades of the 16th century because similar societies had sprung up in Seville around that same time.
[src:caroline-islands/academia-antártica] Because no records documenting the society's gatherings or membership roster remain, little else is known for certain about the Academia.
[src:caroline-islands/academia-antártica] Under the scrutiny of recent post-colonial theorists, the society's name has been interpreted as a deliberately hybrid intended to unite literary customs ("Academia") and spaces where they existed without recognition ("Antártica").
[src:caroline-islands/academia-antártica] The original poetry associated with the Academia, in particular Clarinda's "Discurso en loor de la poesía" ("Discourse in Praise of Poetry"), seems to confirm that its members resented Europe's reluctance to acknowledge as talented the poets who lived and wrote in the American colonies.
[src:caroline-islands/academia-antártica] To modern readers, the Academia's writing may seem more European in style and theme than American.
[src:caroline-islands/academia-antártica] This may be due to the collective's emphasis on the translation and imitation of classical works, the adherence to then-popular Petrarchan tropes, and the general absence of references to indigenous peoples and folklore.
[src:caroline-islands/academia-antártica] Nevertheless, the Academia represents an important step toward the achievement of a Peruvian national literature and its recognition by European intellectuals.
[src:caroline-islands/academia-antártica] This recognition may have come from Spain's most influential author himself, Miguel de Cervantes, who in his *Canto a Calíope* (1583) celebrates the literature generated in Spain's American colonies, though he does not mention the Academia Antártica by name.
[src:caroline-islands/academia-antártica] The most influential of the Academia Antártica's works, the **Primer parte del Parnaso Antártico de obras amotorias** (*Antarctic Parnassus, Part One: Poems of Romance*) was printed in Seville in 1603.
[src:caroline-islands/academia-antártica] Its centerpiece is the new Spanish-language translation of Ovid's *Heroides*, penned by Diego Mexía de Fernangil, a Spaniard who traveled extensively in Mexico and Peru and was a fundamental member of the Academia.
[src:caroline-islands/academia-antártica] The volume also contains Mexía's "El autor a sus amigos" ("From the Author to His Friends"), a narrative of his travels through the Spanish Empire.
[src:caroline-islands/academia-antártica] The publication's cover features an emblem and motto that more or less summarize the Academia's objective (see the facsimile to the right).
[src:caroline-islands/academia-antártica] The motto reads: "*Si Marte llevó a ocaso las dos colunas; Apolo llevó a Antártico las Musas y al Parnaso*" ("If Mars bore the two columns [marking the boundary of known world] off to the West, Apollo carried off the Muses to Parnassus and the Antarctic.").
[src:caroline-islands/academia-antártica] The Antarctic was, in the time of Spanish colonization, a nickname for Peru—the place Mexía says the gods now favor with poetry.
[src:caroline-islands/academia-antártica] Preceding Mexía's translation is a collection of lyric poems written by fellow members of the Academia Antártica and in praise of the author's work.
[src:caroline-islands/academia-antártica] The most notable of these is Clarinda's "*Discurso en loor de la poesía*" ("Discourse in Praise of Poetry"), which also invokes figures from Greek and Roman mythology to lionize the literary genius of colonial Peruvian writers.
[src:caroline-islands/academia-antártica] Due in part to 20th-century feminist and post-colonial analyses, Clarinda's "Discurso" has surpassed Mexía's translation in respect and canonization and has become the Academia's "most celebrated" product.
[src:caroline-islands/academia-antártica] Mexía followed the first part of the *Antarctic Parnassus* series with two subsequent collections.
[src:caroline-islands/academia-antártica] The immediate follow-up, *Segunda parte del Parnaso Antártico de divinos poemas* (*Antarctic Parnassus, Part Two: Poems of the Divine*) has thus far received less critical scrutiny than its predecessor.
[src:caroline-islands/academia-antártica] The final volume, the third part of the *Antarctic Parnassus*, has been lost.
[src:caroline-islands/academia-antártica] The two afore-mentioned publications, and the lost third volume, are the publications most often associated with the Academia Antártica as a collective.
[src:caroline-islands/academia-antártica] However, many of the society's members published other works independently and collectively that also reflect the Academia's influences.
[src:caroline-islands/academia-antártica] These include Carlos de Balboa's *Miscelánea Antártica* (1586) and Diego Dávalos de Figueroa's *Miscelánea Austral* (1602).
[src:caroline-islands/academia-antártica] This list is adopted from the one presented in Sonia Rose's essay, and the categorization is hers; however, the Spanish-language Wikipedia article includes additional names that could not be verified.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Intense extractive activity in the rubber industry, which reached its height in the early 20th century, attracted Brazilians from many regions to the state.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] From the mixture of sulista, southeastern Brazil, nordestino, and indigenous traditions arose a diverse cuisine.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Fluvial transport, concentrated on the Juruá and Moa rivers, in the western part of the state, and the Tarauacá and Envira rivers in the northwest, is the principal form of transportation, especially between November and June.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Heavy seasonal rains frequently make the BR-364 impassable in those months; it usually connects Rio Branco to Cruzeiro do Sul.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] The name, which was given to the territory in 1904, and to the state in 1962, is derived from one of the local rivers, perhaps originates from the Tupi word *a'kir ü* "green river", or from the form *a'kir*, of the Tupi word *ker*, "to sleep, to rest".
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] It is believed more likely to be derived from *Aquiri*, a transliteration by European explorers of the term *Umákürü*, or *Uakiry*, from the Ipurinã dialect.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Another hypothesis is that Acquiri derives from *Yasi'ri*, or *Ysi'ri*, meaning "flowing or swift water".
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] According to one account, agriculturist João Gabriel de Carvalho Melo wrote during an 1878 trip on the Purús River to merchant Viscount of Santo Elias (from Pará), asking him for goods to be sent to the "mouth of the Aquiri River".
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] In Belém, the local merchant or his employees either misinterpreted Gabriel's handwriting, or he spelled the name wrong: the goods and invoice which Gabriel received were marked as having been sent to the Acre River.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Acre possesses some nicknames: the End of Brazil, The Rubber Tree State, the Latex State (from when it was a center of rubber production) and the Western End.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] The native inhabitants of Acre are called *acr**i**ano**s***, in the singular *acr**i**an**o***.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Until the entry according to the Orthographic Agreement of 1990, the correct spelling was *acr**e**an**o*** in the singular and in the plural *acr**e**ano**s***.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] In 2009, with the new orthographic agreement, the change generated controversy between the Academy of Letters of Acre (Academia Acreana de Letras) and the Brazilian Academy of Letters (Academia Brasileira de Letras).
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] The latter said that the change would mean the denial of the state's historical and cultural roots, by changing the last letter of the toponym from "E" to "I".
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] The state of Acre occupies an area of 152,581 km2 (58,912 sq mi) (58,911 mi2) in the extreme west of Brazil.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] It is located at 70º west longitude and at 9º south latitude.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] In Brazil, the state is part of the North Region, forming borders with the states of Amazonas and Rondônia, and with two countries: Peru and Bolivia.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Practically all of the terrain of the state of Acre is part of the low sandstone plateau, or terra firme, morphological unit which dominates most of the Brazilian Amazon.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] These terranes rise, in Acre, from the southeast to the northeast, with very tabular topography in general.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] In the extreme west is found the Serra da Contamana or Serra do Divisor, along the western border, with the highest altitudes in the state (609 m; 1,998 ft).
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] The climate is hot and very humid, of the *Am* type in the Köppen climate classification system, and the monthly average temperatures vary between 24 and 27 °C (75 and 81 °F), being the lowest average of the North Region.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] The rainfall reaches an annual total of 2,100 mm (83 in), with a clear dry season in the months of June, July, and August.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] The Amazon rainforest covers all of the state territory.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Very rich in rubber trees of the most valuable species (*Hevea brasiliensis*) and Brazil nut trees (*Bertholletia excelsa*), the forest guarantees that Acre is the greatest national producer of rubber and nuts.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Acre's principal rivers, mostly navigable during the wet season (the Juruá, Tarauacá, Envira, Purús, Iaco, and Acre), cross the state with almost parallel courses which converge only outside of its territory.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] The largest recorded Black Caiman, measured at 7.7 meters (25 feet) and weighing 1,310 kg (2,890 lb), was shot in Acre in 1965.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] The Amazon represents over half of the planet's remaining rainforests and comprises the largest and most species-rich tract of tropical rainforest in the world.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Wet tropical forests are the most species-rich biome, and tropical forests in the Americas are consistently more species-rich than the wet forests in Africa and Asia.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] As the largest tract of tropical rainforest in the Americas, the Amazonian rainforests have unparalleled biodiversity.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] More than 1/3 of all species in the world live in the Amazon Rainforest.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] The region of present-day Acre is thought to have been inhabited by Pre-Columbian civilizations since at least 2,100 years ago.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Evidence includes complex geoglyphs of this age found in the area.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] The natives who crafted them are believed to have had a relatively advanced knowledge of this technology.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Since at least the early 15th century, the region has been inhabited by peoples who spoke Panoan languages; their territory was geographically close to that of the Inca.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] In the mid-18th century, the region was colonized by the Spanish and became part of the Viceroyalty of Peru.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Following the Peruvian and Bolivian wars of independence, which ended in 1826, the region and large portions around it became part of both Peru and Bolivia respectively, but independent of Spain and both states disputed the territory.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] It was a territory of the short-lived Peru–Bolivian Confederation (1836–1839), until the two countries separated and most of the region returned to Bolivian control.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] The discovery of rubber tree groves in the region in the mid-19th century attracted numerous immigrants, especially from Brazil and Europe, seeking to build on the rubber boom.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Despite the increased numbers of Brazilians, the Treaty of Ayacucho (1867) determined that the region belonged to Bolivia.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] By 1877, Acre's population was composed almost entirely of Brazilians coming from the Northeast.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] In 1899, Brazilian settlers in Acre declared an independent state known as the Republic of Acre.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Bolivia attempted to reassert control, but Brazilian resistance led to armed clashes, culminating in the Acre War.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] On 17 November 1903, the Treaty of Petrópolis was signed, transferring final possession of the region to Brazil.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Acre was incorporated as a Brazilian territory divided into three departments.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Brazil acquired the land for two million pounds sterling, with the territory taken from Mato Grosso under terms that also facilitated the construction of the Madeira-Mamoré railway.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Once the Acre War was over, Peru did not recognize the annexation of Acre until 1909, with the Velarde-Río Branco Treaty, where the borders between Peru and Brazil were defined.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] It was signed in Rio de Janeiro, on September 8, 1909, by the Minister of Foreign Affairs of Brazil, Baron of Rio Branco, and the plenipotentiary minister of Peru in Brazil, Hernán Velarde, by President Augusto B.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Leguía (first government) then ruled in Peru, and in Brazil by the president Nilo Pecanha, in order to solve the border problems between Peru and Brazil.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] On June 15, 1962, it was elevated to the category of state, and was the first to be governed by a woman, Iolanda Fleming, a teacher.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] During the early twentieth century, rubber seedlings were taken to Southeast Asia, where competitive plantations were established, reducing the importance of the Amazon in production.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] During the Second World War, Japanese forces took over the rubber tree groves of British Malaya.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Acre was called on to produce rubber for the Allied war effort.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] The Rubber Soldiers, natives mostly of the Ceará plantation, increased production and provided critical supplies to the Allies.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Acre's decisive contribution to the Allied victory may have helped Brazil attract North American investment to form the National Steel Company (Companhia Siderúrgica Nacional) in the postwar era.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] This company aided in the industrialization of the Central-south, which did not yet possess basic heavy industries.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] On April 4, 2008, Acre won a judicial debate with the state of Amazonas in relation to the dispute surrounding the Cunha Gomes Line.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] It annexed part of the municipalities of Envira, Guajará, Boca do Acre, Pauini, Eirunepé and Ipixuna.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] The territorial redefinition consolidated the incorporation of 1.2 million hectares of the Liberdade, Gregório, and Mogno forest complex to the territory of Acre, which corresponds to 11,583.87 km2 (4,472.56 sq mi).
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Since the 1970s, numerous geoglyphs, major geometric earthworks, have been discovered on deforested land in Acre, and dated to between 1–1250 AD.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] These are cited as evidence of complex Pre-Columbian societies.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] The BBC's *Unnatural Histories* explored studies of this area, concluding that the Amazon rainforest, rather than being a pristine "wilderness", has been shaped by man for at least 11,000 years.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Traditional ancient practices included forest gardening.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Ondemar Dias is credited as the first to discover the geoglyphs in 1977.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Alceu Ranzi expanded their findings by flying over Acre.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] During the 17th century, Portuguese expeditions reached many of the far ends of present-day Brazil.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] The expansion of the exploration to the west followed, and they reached lands under control by the Spanish colonies.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] The two nations negotiated to establish their territories, under the Treaties of Madrid (1750) and San Ildefonso (1777).
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Both of the treaties were based on the explorations of Portuguese *bandeirante* Manoel Félix de Lima of the Guaporé and Madeira river basins.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] The treaties established the riverbeds of the Mamoré and Guaporé to their maximum western limits on the left bank of the Javari as the border between the Spanish and Portuguese territories.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] The Portuguese created the new royal captaincy of Mato Grosso (1751), stimulating settlement toward the frontier.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] New centers developed: Vila Bela (1752) on the banks of the Guaporé, Vila Maria (1778) on the Paraguay River, and Casalvasco (1783).
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Until the mid-19th century, there was little effort to settle the area systematically.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] At that time, the great virgin source of rubber attracted commercial interest, and development followed.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] The empire was directed towards agricultural exports, based on coffee as the most important commodity.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] The territories of the extreme west were unknown and usually overlooked.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] For example, although Cândido Mendes de Almeida's *Atlas of the Empire of Brazil* (1868), was considered a model of its time, geographers knew nothing of the Acre River and its principal tributaries, which did not appear at all in the atlas.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Some few armed bands of Brazilian explorers exploited the rural and unpopulated region, not knowing and little interested in whether they were "controlled" by Brazil, Peru, or Bolivia.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] But the rubber boom of the mid-19th century, stimulated exploration by various expeditions to survey this resource and develop a plan for colonial settlement.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] For the most part, these expeditions took place on Bolivian land.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Exploitative activities, the industrial importance of the rubber reserves, and the penetration of Brazilian colonists in the region raised the attention of Bolivia, which solicited a better fixation of boundaries.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] After much failed negotiation, in 1867 the Treaty of Ayacucho was signed, which recognized the colonial *uti possidetis*, or use of that territory by Brazil.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] A border was established parallel to the confluence of the Beni and Mamoré rivers, running eastward to the headwaters of the Javari River, even though the source of this river was not yet known.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] As the price of rubber rose in the market, the demand for it grew.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Plantations multiplied in the valleys of the Acre, Purús and, farther west, the Tarauacá.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] In the year 1873–1874, in the drainage basin of the Purús, the population rose from around one thousand to four thousand inhabitants.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] The Brazilian imperial government, already sensitive to the resulting offerings of rubber, considered the entire valley of the Purús to be Brazilian.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] In the second half of the 19th century, disturbances were registered in the demographic and geo-economic balance of the empire.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] The coffee boom in the south attracted financial resources and workers, to detriment of the northeast.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] The growing impoverishment of that region stimulated migratory waves to the states of Rio de Janeiro, Minas Gerais, and São Paulo.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] The movement of population became particularly active during the prolonged drought of the northeastern interior, from 1877 to 1880.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Hundreds of Ceará indigenous people headed for the rubber plantations in search of work.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] The Cearense migration reached the banks of the Juruá and accelerated the occupation of land which Bolivia would later reclaim.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] The great fluvial rivers and their tributary systems were full of small ship fleets transporting colonists, goods, and supply material to the most isolated centers.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] The governments of Amazonas and Pará quickly established *supply houses*, which financed various types of operations, guaranteed credit, and promoted the commercial incentive of the rubber tree groves.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] The rubber race had the frantic urgency of gold rushes of the 18th century.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] The situation drew the attention of the government to the economic use and development of an almost completely unknown area.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] The activities of private businesses would enable the government to incorporate the new region.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] In 1890, José Manuel Pando, a Bolivian official, alerted his government to the fact that more than three hundred rubber plantations had been developed in the Jura basin, and most were occupied by Brazilians on what was nominally Bolivian territory.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] The Brazilian penetration had advanced west from the 64th meridian to beyond the 72nd, in an extension of one thousand kilometers, despite the borders having been established.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] The Treaty of 1867 limited Brazil to land above the confluence of the Beni and Mamoré rivers.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] In 1895 a new commission to define the borders was created.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] The Brazilian representative, Gregório Taumaturgo de Azevedo, resigned after verifying that the ratification of the Treaty of 1867 would harm the Brazilian rubber gatherers already settled in Bolivian territory.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] In 1899, the Bolivians established an administrative post in Puerto Alonso, exacting taxes and customs duties upon Brazilian activities.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] The following year, Brazil accepted the sovereignty of Bolivia in the zone, when it officially recognized the old boundaries at the confluence of the Beni and Mamoré rivers.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Distant from the diplomatic process, the rubber workers judged their interests to have been cheated, and initiated insurrection movements.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Some of this was in response to brutal treatment and abuse by forces managed by the major rubber companies.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] In the same year that Bolivia established administration in Puerto Alonso (1899), two serious uprisings occurred.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] In April, a Cearense lawyer, José Carvalho, led an armed movement, which culminated in the expulsion of the Bolivian authorities.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Shortly thereafter, Bolivia began negotiations with an Anglo-American trust, the *Bolivian Syndicate*, in order to promote, with exceptional force (exacting of taxes, armed force), the political and economic incorporation of Acre into its territory.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] The governor of Amazonas, Ramalho Júnior, informed of the agreement by a functionary of the Bolivian consulate in Belém, Luis Gálvez Rodríguez de Arias, sent military contingents forward to occupy Puerto Alonso.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Gálvez proclaimed the independence of Acre, in the form of a republic.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] He became its president with the acquiescence of the rubber gatherers.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Under protests from Bolivia, President Campos Sales abolished the ephemeral republic (March 1900).
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Bolivians, reinstated in the region, suffered in 1900 from the assault of the so-called Floriano Peixoto expedition, or "expedition of the poets".
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] It was made up of intellectual bohemians from Manaus.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Following brief fighting in the area surrounding Puerto Alonso, the expedition was completely scattered.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Ultimately, the Bolivian government signed a contract with the *Bolivian Syndicate* (July 1901).
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] The Brazilian congress, shocked by the arbitrariness of the act, took measures, canceling commercial accords and navigation between the two countries, and suspending the right of travel to Bolivia.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] At the same time, Brazilians organized a large armed assault on the disputed area.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] The operations were led by a former student of the Military School of Rio Grande do Sul (Escola Militar do Rio Grande do Sul), José Plácido de Castro.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] The rubber gatherers occupied the village of Xapuri in Alto Acre (August 1902), and took Bolivian officials into custody.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Finally, Plácido de Castro's forces besieged Puerto Alonso, proclaiming the Independent State of Acre, after the capitulation of Bolivian troops (February 1903).
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] José Plácido de Castro was proclaimed governor of the new Independent State of Acre, and he had to discuss the question of borders in the diplomatic sphere.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] The Baron of Rio Branco, who had just assumed the role of Brazil's Minister of External Relations, immediately opened channels which were meant to have put an end to the question.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] The simplest problem, with the *Bolivian Syndicate*, was resolved by Brazil paying one hundred and ten thousand pounds to renounce the contract (February 1903).
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Next, commercial relations were reestablished with Bolivia, while a part of the territory on the upper Purús and Juruá, militarily occupied in March 1903, was declared litigious.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Bolivia finally agreed to cede to Brazil an area of 142,800 km2 (55,100 sq mi), in exchange for two million pounds sterling, paid in two installments.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Brazil committed to the construction of a Madeira-Mamoré Railway, connecting Porto Velho to Guajará-Mirim, at the confluence of the Beni and Madeira rivers.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] These actions were ratified in the Treaty of Petrópolis (November 17, 1903), through which Brazil acquired the future territory, now state of Acre.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Peru had also claimed sovereignty over the entire territory of Acre and part of the state of Amazonas, based on historic colonial titles.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] After armed conflicts between Brazilians and Peruvians on the upper Purús and Juruá, a joint administration was established in those regions (1904).
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] The studies to determine the borders proceeded until the end of 1909, when a treaty was signed that completed the political integration of Acre into Brazilian territory.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Exercising a prominent role in national exports until 1913, when rubber was introduced to European and North American markets, Acre enjoyed a period of great prosperity.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] At the start of the 20th century, in a period of less than ten years, it grew to have more than 50,000 inhabitants.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] From 1946 on, the federal government undertook actions to revive the economy of the Amazon Basin, and to include it in regional development projects.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] The departmental administration was exercised until 1921 by mayors appointed by the President of Brazil.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] At that time the arrangements were altered, passing the administration to a governor.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] The second Constitution of Brazil (1934) conceded to Acre the right to elect representatives to the National Congress of Brazil.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] During the Estado Novo (New State) political ideas involving the valorization of the interior took hold, with the intention of promoting the articulation of more isolated areas.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Thereafter, the vote of 1946 commended the channeling of budgetary resources from the Union to the Amazon, determining that the Territory of Acre would be elevated to the condition of state as soon as its revenue reached the equivalent of the lowest state tax exaction.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] In the 1960s, the second cycle of efforts to accelerate the progress of the Amazon area was begun with the Superintendency of the Development of the Amazon (Superintendência do Desenvolvimento da Amazônia or SUDAM, 1966).
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Planning politics developed, therefore, destined to correct the demographic, economic, and political distortions of national integration.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] According to the IBGE of 2022, there were 830,018 people residing in the state. making Acre the third least populated state.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] The population density was 4.5 inh./km2.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] As of 2022, Acre is one of two states in Brazil where Protestants outnumber Catholics.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Portuguese is the official national language, and thus the primary language taught in schools.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] English and Spanish are also part of the official high school curriculum.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] The service sector is the largest component of GDP at 66%, followed by the industrial sector at 28.1%.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Agriculture represents 5.9%, of GDP (2004).
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Acre exports: wood 85.6%, poultry (chicken and wild turkey) 4.7%, wood products 1.7% (2002).
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Share of the Brazilian economy: 0.2% (2005).
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Rio Branco International Airport is located in a rural zone of the municipality of Rio Branco, in the state of Acre.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] It was opened on November 2, 1999, with a unique characteristic: it moved 22 kilometers away from the previous airport site.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Rio Branco Airport serves domestic and international flights (by scheduled carriers and air taxi firms) along with general and military aviation.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] The terminal can receive 270 thousand passengers a year and serves an average of 14 daily operations.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Cruzeiro do Sul International Airport is located 18 kilometers away from the city center, which helps access to the Alto Juruá region.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] It was opened on October 28, 1970, and absorbed by Infraero on March 31, 1980.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] The airport infrastructure was built in 1976 by the municipal government.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] In 1994, the runway was completely renovated.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] There are domestic airports at Tarauacá, Sena Madureira and Brasiléia.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Rio Branco provides visitors and residents with various sport activities.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] The Arena da Floresta stadium in Rio Branco was one of the 18 candidates to host games in the 2014 FIFA World Cup, which was held in Brazil, but did not make it to the final 12 chosen.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Despite being the only state that fought to be Brazilian (Acre War), Acre's culture is similar to that of other Northern Brazilian states, however, there is a high consumption of Northeastern Brazilian culture.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] The ritual implies in drinking a tea, including children and the elderly.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] The members wear uniforms and sing the hymnal.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] The best-known dish consumed by Acreans is called Baixaria.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] The typical food uses duck, tucupi, cassava flour and pirarucu fish, in addition to the huge variety of Amazonian fruits inherited from the Indigenous peoples.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] Some singers, activists and artists from Acre: João Donato, Sansão Campos Pereira, Chico Mendes, Sergio Souto and Tião Natureza.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] It is a variation of the flags used by the secessionist state of Acre, with the yellow and green parts exchanged and mirrored.
[src:caroline-islands/acre-state] The yellow color symbolizes peace, green hope, and the star symbolizes the light which guided those who worked to make Acre a state of Brazil.
[src:caroline-islands/adams-onís-treaty] The **Adams–Onís Treaty** was an agreement between Spain and the United States, signed February 22, 1819, by John Quincy Adams and Luis de Onís respectively.
[src:caroline-islands/adams-onís-treaty] The US acquired Florida while renouncing claims to Spanish Texas and establishing its first transcontinental boundary.
[src:caroline-islands/adams-onís-treaty] The provisions of the treaty remained in full effect only until August 24, 1821, when the Treaty of Córdoba acknowledged Mexican independence from Spain.
[src:caroline-islands/adams-onís-treaty] In the 1828 Treaty of Limits (Mexico–United States), the border defined by the Adams–Onís Treaty was recognized as the boundary between Mexico and the US, although following the 1845 Texas annexation, it was amended again by the Treaty of Guadalupe Hidalgo.
[src:caroline-islands/adams-onís-treaty] The Adams–Onís Treaty was formally terminated in 1902.
[src:caroline-islands/adams-onís-treaty] Pinckney's Treaty of 1795 established borders between the United States and Spanish Florida, but expansion by American settlers into this region led to ongoing disputes between the countries.
[src:caroline-islands/adams-onís-treaty] The 1803 Louisiana Purchase caused further arguments over whether the new boundary to the south ran along the Sabine River, or the Rio Grande.
[src:caroline-islands/adams-onís-treaty] The outbreak of the Peninsular War in 1807 and the Spanish American wars of independence in 1808, undermined Madrid's ability to retain its American territories.
[src:caroline-islands/adams-onís-treaty] Between 1810 and 1813, the US took advantage to annex West Florida in piecemeal fashion from the Mississippi east to the Perdido River, the modern state boundary with Alabama.
[src:caroline-islands/adams-onís-treaty] During the first of the Seminole Wars from 1817 to 1818, the US occupied the rest of Florida, presenting John Quincy Adams, then Secretary of State, an opportunity to negotiate favorable terms.
[src:caroline-islands/adams-onís-treaty] His policy was to simultaneously avoid foreign commitments, but to also establish the US as the preponderant power on the North American continent.
[src:caroline-islands/adams-onís-treaty] This required the elimination as far as possible of competing Spanish, Russian and British interests in the region, and extending the limits of American power to the Pacific.
[src:caroline-islands/adams-onís-treaty] These principles were set out in more detail in the 1823 Monroe Doctrine.
[src:caroline-islands/adams-onís-treaty] By 1819, Spain was prepared to accept the loss of Florida in exchange for a firm border in Texas.
[src:caroline-islands/adams-onís-treaty] For his part, Adams saw an opportunity to remove outstanding Spanish claims in the Western United States, and establish the US' first transcontinental boundary.
[src:caroline-islands/adams-onís-treaty] Despite their increasingly tenuous position in New Spain, the Madrid government was prepared to make concessions, hoping to regain them at a later date.
[src:caroline-islands/adams-onís-treaty] Negotiations were held in Washington, D.C., led by Adams for the United States, and Luis de Onís, the Spanish ambassador, resulting in a final agreement of 16 articles.
[src:caroline-islands/adams-onís-treaty] Key provisions included Article 2, transferring East and West Florida to the US, and Article 3, defining the southern border between the two countries, while Spain withdrew historic claims to the Oregon Country.
[src:caroline-islands/adams-onís-treaty] Other terms included an agreement by the US government to compensate American settlers for alleged losses inflicted by the Spanish, the continuation of Pinckney's Treaty, and most favoured nation privileges for Spanish traders in Pensacola and St.
[src:caroline-islands/adams-onís-treaty] Senate approved the treaty unanimously on February 24, 1819, but Madrid delayed ratification until October 1820, hoping to dissuade the US from supporting anti-Spanish revolutionaries.
[src:caroline-islands/adams-onís-treaty] As a result of the delay, the Senate had to vote a second time, at which point Henry Clay and others demanded the cession of Texas in addition.
[src:caroline-islands/adams-onís-treaty] This proposal was defeated and the treaty officially made effective on February 22, 1821.
[src:caroline-islands/adams-onís-treaty] In accordance with Article 11, the US government set up a commission to handle claims made by private American citizens against Spain, which distributed around $5 million prior to its dissolution in 1824.
[src:caroline-islands/adams-onís-treaty] For the United States, this Treaty (and the Treaty of 1818 with Britain agreeing to joint control of the Pacific Northwest) meant that its claimed territory now extended far west from the Mississippi River to the Pacific Ocean.
[src:caroline-islands/adams-onís-treaty] For Spain, it meant that it kept its colony of Texas and also kept a buffer zone between its colonies in California and New Mexico and the U.S. territories.
[src:caroline-islands/adams-onís-treaty] Many historians consider the Treaty to be a great achievement for the U.S., as time validated Adams's vision that it would allow the U.S. to open trade with the Orient across the Pacific.
[src:caroline-islands/adams-onís-treaty] Informally this new border has been called the "Step Boundary", although the step-like shape of the boundary was not apparent for several decades—the source of the Arkansas, believed to be near the 42nd parallel north, was not known until John C.
[src:caroline-islands/adams-onís-treaty] Frémont located it in the 1840s, hundreds of miles south of the 42nd parallel.
[src:caroline-islands/adams-onís-treaty] Spain finally recognized the independence of Mexico with the Treaty of Córdoba signed on August 24, 1821.
[src:caroline-islands/adams-onís-treaty] While Mexico was not initially a party to the Adams–Onís Treaty, in 1831 Mexico ratified the treaty by agreeing to the 1828 Treaty of Limits with the U.S.
[src:caroline-islands/adams-onís-treaty] With the Russo-American Treaty of 1824, the Russian Empire ceded its claims south of parallel 54°40′ north to the United States.
[src:caroline-islands/adams-onís-treaty] With the Treaty of Saint Petersburg in 1825, Russia set the southern border of Alaska on the same parallel in exchange for the Russian right to trade south of that border and the British right to navigate north of that border.
[src:caroline-islands/adams-onís-treaty] This set the absolute limits of the Oregon Country/Columbia District between the 42nd parallel north and the parallel 54°40′ north west of the Continental Divide.
[src:caroline-islands/adams-onís-treaty] By the mid-1830s, a controversy developed regarding the border with Texas, during which the United States demonstrated that the Sabine and Neches rivers had been switched on maps, moving the frontier in favor of Mexico.
[src:caroline-islands/adams-onís-treaty] As a consequence, the eastern boundary of Texas was not firmly established until the independence of the Republic of Texas in 1836.
[src:caroline-islands/adams-onís-treaty] It was not agreed upon by the United States and Mexico until the Treaty of Guadalupe Hidalgo in 1848, which concluded the Mexican–American War.
[src:caroline-islands/adams-onís-treaty] That treaty also formalized the cession by Mexico of Alta California and today's American Southwest, except for the territory of the later Gadsden Purchase of 1854.
[src:caroline-islands/adams-onís-treaty] Another dispute occurred after Texas joined the Union.
[src:caroline-islands/adams-onís-treaty] The treaty stated that the boundary between the French claims on the north and the Spanish claims on the south was Rio Roxo de Natchitoches (Red River) until it reached the 100th meridian, as noted on the John Melish map of 1818.
[src:caroline-islands/adams-onís-treaty] But, the 100th meridian on the Melish map was marked some 90 miles (140 km) east of the true 100th meridian, and the Red River forked about 50 miles (80 km) east of the 100th meridian.
[src:caroline-islands/adams-onís-treaty] Texas claimed the land south of the North Fork, and the United States claimed the land north of the South Fork (later called the Prairie Dog Town Fork Red River).
[src:caroline-islands/adams-onís-treaty] In 1860, Texas organized the area as Greer County.
[src:caroline-islands/adams-onís-treaty] The matter was not settled until a United States Supreme Court ruling in 1896 upheld federal claims to the territory, after which it was added to the Oklahoma Territory.
[src:caroline-islands/adams-onís-treaty] The treaty gave rise to a later border dispute between the states of Oregon and California, which remains unresolved.
[src:caroline-islands/adams-onís-treaty] Upon statehood in 1850, California established the 42nd parallel as its constitutional de jure border as it had existed since 1819 when the territory was part of Spanish Mexico.
[src:caroline-islands/adams-onís-treaty] In an 1868–1870 border survey following the admission of Oregon as a state, errors were made in demarcating and marking the Oregon-California border, creating a dispute that continues to this day.
[src:caroline-islands/adams-onís-treaty] In 2020, a hoax appeared in Spain according to which, in 2055, the Adams–Onís Treaty would expire and Florida would be returned to Spain by the United States, which is false.
[src:caroline-islands/adams-onís-treaty] The previous Anglo-American Convention of 1818 meant that both American and British citizens could settle land north of the 42nd parallel and west of the Continental Divide.
[src:caroline-islands/adams-onís-treaty] The United States now had a firm foothold on the Pacific Coast and could commence settlement of the jointly occupied Oregon Country (known as the Columbia District to the British government).
[src:caroline-islands/adams-onís-treaty] The Russian Empire also claimed this entire region as part of Russian America.
[src:caroline-islands/adelaide-hills] The **Adelaide Hills** region is located in the southern Mount Lofty Ranges east of the city of Adelaide in the state of South Australia.
[src:caroline-islands/adelaide-hills] The largest town in the area, Mount Barker, is one of Australia's fastest-growing towns.
[src:caroline-islands/adelaide-hills] Before British colonisation of South Australia, the area was inhabited by the Peramangk people.
[src:caroline-islands/adelaide-hills] The Adelaide Hills wine region comprises areas of the Adelaide Hills above 300 m (980 ft).
[src:caroline-islands/adelaide-hills] The Adelaide Hills were among the first areas of South Australia to be settled by European settlers.
[src:caroline-islands/adelaide-hills] A number of towns in the Hills were started as German settlements; Hahndorf and Lobethal are two examples.
[src:caroline-islands/adelaide-hills] The original town names and architecture still reflect this.
[src:caroline-islands/adelaide-hills] Descendants of these first settlers and others of German origin still reside in the area.
[src:caroline-islands/adelaide-hills] Wood was harvested by woodsmen in the hills and carted to the city for building new buildings from the earliest days of the colony of South Australia.
[src:caroline-islands/adelaide-hills] The hills were then named "the Tiers", and the timber merchants "tiersmen".
[src:caroline-islands/adelaide-hills] The first pub in the East End of Adelaide, built at 233–237 Grenfell Street, was known as the Woodman (later being rebuilt as The Producers Hotel).
[src:caroline-islands/adelaide-hills] This explains the strong German cultural connection seen in the number of Lutheran churches, Lutheran schools which often have German on the curriculum, and the number of older residents who still speak German.
[src:caroline-islands/adelaide-hills] Some customs have grown, such as the Lobethal Christmas lights which began in the 1950s.
[src:caroline-islands/adelaide-hills] Today, only one railway goes through the Adelaide Hills: the Adelaide to Melbourne railway line, which was first built in the 1870s and has had only some major realignments since (the most significant of which was the boring of a new tunnel at Sleeps Hill).
[src:caroline-islands/adelaide-hills] Commuter passenger train services used to run from the city to the town of Bridgewater in the heart of the hills but were cut back to terminate at Belair in 1987.
[src:caroline-islands/adelaide-hills] For many Adelaide residents, a drive through the hills is a popular pastime, particularly due to proximity to the city and other suburbs.
[src:caroline-islands/adelaide-hills] With Adelaide being a linear city extending 90 kilometres (56 mi) north to south, the hills are within 20 kilometres (12 mi) of the majority of residents.
[src:caroline-islands/adelaide-hills] The Adelaide Hills region is close enough to commute to the city, yet is the gateway to the country, so residents enjoy the best of both worlds – the country community life and the convenience of the city.
[src:caroline-islands/adelaide-hills] Desirability of the area has increased, particularly since realignment of the road and construction of the Heysen Tunnels on the South Eastern Freeway improved road access.
[src:caroline-islands/adelaide-hills] The tunnels, completed in 1999, are named after Sir Hans Heysen, an eminent local landscape painter whose home and studio, "The Cedars", has been maintained as a cultural site located near Hahndorf.
[src:caroline-islands/adelaide-hills] To this day, Hahndorf itself supports a thriving community of artists and craftspeople, either in the town or nearby countryside.
[src:caroline-islands/adelaide-hills] The Adelaide Hills wine region includes all areas of the Hills above 300 m (980 ft).
[src:caroline-islands/adelaide-hills] The elevation leads to cooler nights during the warm summer months, important for increasing the flavour of wines during the ripening season, and higher rainfall.
[src:caroline-islands/adelaide-hills] The Adelaide Hills region is one of the oldest wine region within Australia.
[src:caroline-islands/adelaide-hills] The first vines were planted in the Hills at Echunga by John Barton Hack in 1839, three years after South Australia was declared a province, with the first wines produced in 1843.
[src:caroline-islands/adelaide-hills] The Mount Lofty area, home to Adelaide's television transmission towers, has a lookout area, restaurant and the fire-spotting tower that used to be run by the Country Fire Service.
[src:caroline-islands/adelaide-hills] It is also home to Mount Lofty Botanic Gardens.
[src:caroline-islands/adelaide-hills] Gumeracha is home to the largest rocking horse in the world, standing at 18.3 metres (60.0 ft) (approximately the height of a six-storey building) and open to the public, it serves to advertise an adjacent wooden toy factory and wildlife park.
[src:caroline-islands/adelaide-hills] The National Motor Museum is at Birdwood.
[src:caroline-islands/adelaide-hills] The National Motor Museum is the endpoint of the "Bay to Birdwood" event, in which up to 5,000 motor vehicles are driven by their owners from Glenelg past the city and through the hills to finish at the museum, a distance of 70 km (43 mi), where a festival is held.
[src:caroline-islands/adelaide-hills] There are two Bay to Birdwood events held on alternate years: the Run, held on even-numbered years, for vehicles manufactured up to 31 December 1959, while the Classic, held on odd-numbered years, is for vehicles manufactured between 1 January 1956 and 31 December 1986.
[src:caroline-islands/adelaide-hills] The Tour Down Under is a major annual sporting event, which makes use of some of South Australia's most popular cycling locations, including the Hills.
[src:caroline-islands/adelaide-hills] The area is home to the annual Medieval Fair held at Gumeracha across one weekend every April, and the English Ale Festival, also annually held each May.
[src:caroline-islands/adelaide-hills] Highlights of the Medieval Fair include live jousting tournaments held on horseback, blacksmithing and dance demonstrations, needlework and costume creation, and authentic music provided by wandering troubadours.
[src:caroline-islands/adelaide-hills] The genesis and popularity of these two colourful festivals, where patrons are encouraged to come in costume, springs from the relatively large numbers of British expatriates who reside in the Hills.
[src:caroline-islands/adelaide-hills] Throughout the year there are folk music sessions and concerts held in various small towns like Mt Pleasant, Mylor and Balhannah – connected with this same cultural community.
[src:caroline-islands/adelaide-hills] The Hills region includes the Cleland National Park, and within it the Cleland Wildlife Park with its free-roaming kangaroos, wallabies and emus.
[src:caroline-islands/adelaide-hills] The park also has enclosed areas for dingos, koalas, native birds and snakes, and is a popular destination for school groups as well as interstate and international visitors.
[src:caroline-islands/adelaide-hills] Many native species of fauna can be encountered within the hills region.
[src:caroline-islands/adelaide-hills] Among the more common species include the kookaburra, tawny frogmouth, southern brown bandicoot, kangaroo, brown tree frog, and bearded dragon.
[src:caroline-islands/adelaide-hills] Several of the less common species include the antechinus (Morialta Conservation Park), heath monitor (Scott Creek Conservation Park) and the very rare inland carpet python (greater Mount Barker region).
[src:caroline-islands/adelaide-hills] Many walking trails, including a portion of the Heysen Trail and bike trails, including the start of the Mawson Trail abound within the Hills.
[src:caroline-islands/adelaide-hills] The Heysen Trail itself extends from the tip of the Fleurieau Peninsula, through the Adelaide Hills and on up to the Flinders Ranges, three hours drive north of Adelaide.
[src:caroline-islands/adelaide-hills] Birds found in the Hills include parrots such as the Adelaide rosella, rainbow and musk lorikeets as well as large cockatoos like the Major Mitchell, and the yellow-tailed black cockatoo.
[src:caroline-islands/adelaide-hills] Smaller resident species include the superb blue wren and eastern spinebill.
[src:caroline-islands/adelaide-hills] Sporting and recreational activities are also popular in the hills region, with sports such as Australian rules football, cricket and soccer having very strong participation rates.
[src:caroline-islands/adelaide-hills] The Basket Range Oval is home to the Basket Range Cricket Club.
[src:caroline-islands/adelaide-hills] A small independent weekly newspaper, *The Courier*, is published in Mount Barker and serves many Hills towns.
[src:caroline-islands/adelaide-hills] Founded in 1880, the paper has never missed a print run.
[src:caroline-islands/adelaide-hills] It has been in the hands of the same family, the Marstons, since 1954, with a circulation of 7,500 as of May 2020, down from 15,000 in its heyday in the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:caroline-islands/adelaide-hills] It is generally a few degrees cooler in the Hills than in Adelaide city centre and Plains.
[src:caroline-islands/adelaide-hills] The days are warm in January and February, but the region generally experiences cool nights.
[src:caroline-islands/adelaide-hills] This significant diurnal variation results in cool mean daily temperatures even in summer.
[src:caroline-islands/adelaide-hills] The area receives a light snowfall approximately once every three to four years, occasionally enough to stay on the ground for half a day, and large amounts of hail are more likely to fall here than on the Plains.
[src:caroline-islands/admiralty-islands-languages] The **Admiralty Islands languages** are a group of some thirty Oceanic languages spoken on the Admiralty Islands.
[src:caroline-islands/admiralty-islands-languages] They may include Yapese, which has proven difficult to classify.
[src:caroline-islands/admiralty-islands-languages] As noted, Yapese and Nguluwan may be part of the Admiralty Islands languages as well.
[src:caroline-islands/admiralty-islands] The **Admiralty Islands** are an archipelago group of 40 islands in the Bismarck Archipelago, to the north of New Guinea in the South Pacific Ocean.
[src:caroline-islands/admiralty-islands] These are also sometimes known as the **Manus Islands**, after the largest island of the chain.
[src:caroline-islands/admiralty-islands] These rainforest-covered islands constitute Manus Province, the smallest and least-populous province of Papua New Guinea, in its Islands Region.
[src:caroline-islands/admiralty-islands] The province had a population of 60,485 at the 2011 Census.
[src:caroline-islands/admiralty-islands] Many of the smaller Admiralty Islands are atolls and uninhabited.
[src:caroline-islands/admiralty-islands] The larger islands in the center of the group are Manus Island and Los Negros Island.
[src:caroline-islands/admiralty-islands] The other larger islands are Tong Island, Pak Island, Rambutyo Island and Lou Island to the east, Mbuke Island to the south and Bipi Island to the west of Manus Island.
[src:caroline-islands/admiralty-islands] Baluan Island, to the south of Manus Island, is the main island of the Pam Islands, where the Baluan-Pam language is spoken.
[src:caroline-islands/admiralty-islands] Other islands that have been noted as significant places in the history of Manus include Ndrova Island, Pityilu Island and Ponam Island.
[src:caroline-islands/admiralty-islands] The temperature of the Admiralty Islands varies little throughout the year, reaching daily highs of 30–32 °C (86–90 °F) and 20–24 °C (68–75 °F) at night.
[src:caroline-islands/admiralty-islands] Average annual rainfall is 3,382 mm (133 in) and is somewhat seasonal, with June–August being the wettest months.
[src:caroline-islands/admiralty-islands] Manus reaches an elevation of 700 m (2,300 ft) and is volcanic in origin and probably broke through the ocean's surface in the late Miocene, 8–10 million years ago.
[src:caroline-islands/admiralty-islands] The substrate of the island is either directly volcanic or from uplifted coral limestone.
[src:caroline-islands/admiralty-islands] The main town in the islands is Lorengau on Manus, connected by road to an airport on nearby Los Negros Island, otherwise transport around the islands is by boat.
[src:caroline-islands/admiralty-islands] There is little tourism, although the seas are attractive to divers, including Jean-Michel Cousteau who spent time on nearby Wuvulu Island in the 1970s.
[src:caroline-islands/admiralty-islands] Due to the isolated location, the rain forests of the Admiralty Islands are home to rare and endemic species of birds, bats and other animals, and are considered a separate ecoregion, the **Admiralty Islands lowland rain forests**.
[src:caroline-islands/admiralty-islands] The majority of the forests on Manus still remain, but some of the smaller islands have been cleared for coconut farming.
[src:caroline-islands/admiralty-islands] The typical tree species are various *Calophyllum* and *Sararanga* species.
[src:caroline-islands/admiralty-islands] The 58.5 km2 (22.6 sq mi) Ndrolowa Wildlife Management Area was created in March 1985 south of Lorengau on Manus Island and contains both terrestrial and marine regions.
[src:caroline-islands/admiralty-islands] A further 240 km2 (93 sq mi) protected area has been established around the highest mountain on Manus, Mount Dremsel, but the level of protection remains undetermined in the UNEP World Database on Protected Areas.
[src:caroline-islands/admiralty-islands] Three of the bird species endemic to Admiralty Islands have been listed as vulnerable in the IUCN Red List: Manus fantail (*Rhipidura semirubra*), superb pitta (*Pitta superba*) and Manus masked owl (*Tyto manusi*), and the Manus dwarf kingfisher (*Ceyx dispar*) listed as near threatened.
[src:caroline-islands/admiralty-islands] Three other birds are endemic to Admiralty Islands but are classified as non-threatened or least concern: white-naped friarbird (*Philemon albitorques*), Manus monarch (*Monarcha infelix*) and Manus hawk owl (*Ninox meeki*).
[src:caroline-islands/admiralty-islands] The islands are home to two endemic *Cornufer* frogs (*Cornufer admiraltiensis* and *Cornufer latro*) and four lizards, while the emerald green snail of Manus was the first terrestrial snail to be listed as vulnerable by the IUCN.
[src:caroline-islands/admiralty-islands] Along with New Guinea, the Bismarck Archipelago and the Solomon Islands Archipelago, the Admiralty Islands were first inhabited approximately 40,000 years ago, in the initial wave of migration out of Southeast Asia that also populated Australia.
[src:caroline-islands/admiralty-islands] This early society appears to have cultivated taro, and to have deliberately introduced wild animals from New Guinea such as bandicoots and large rats.
[src:caroline-islands/admiralty-islands] Obsidian was gathered and traded throughout the Admiralty Islands archipelago.
[src:caroline-islands/admiralty-islands] The Lapita culture arose around 3,500 years ago, and its extent ranged from the Admiralty Islands to Tonga and Samoa.
[src:caroline-islands/admiralty-islands] Its origins are contested, but it may well have been a product of another wave of migration from Southeast Asia.
[src:caroline-islands/admiralty-islands] Lapita society featured renowned pottery, stilt houses, the introduction of domestic animals such as pigs, dogs, and chickens, and substantial developments in agriculture and boat technology, allowing long-distance trade to develop.
[src:caroline-islands/admiralty-islands] Lapita society, as a distinct culture and extended trade network, collapsed around 2,000 years ago.
[src:caroline-islands/admiralty-islands] The first European to visit the islands was the Spanish navigator Álvaro de Saavedra when trying to return from Tidore to New Spain in the summer of 1528.
[src:caroline-islands/admiralty-islands] Saavedra charted Manus as *Urays la Grande*.
[src:caroline-islands/admiralty-islands] Its visit was also reported in 1616 by the Dutch navigator Willem Schouten.
[src:caroline-islands/admiralty-islands] The name 'Admiralty Islands' was devised by Captain Philip Carteret of the British Royal Navy in 1767.
[src:caroline-islands/admiralty-islands] Between 1884 and 1914 the area was administered as a German colony.
[src:caroline-islands/admiralty-islands] In November 1914, the islands were occupied by troops of the Australian Naval and Military Expeditionary Force landed from the SS *Siar*.
[src:caroline-islands/admiralty-islands] A few shots fired from a machine gun on *Siar* over the heads of the tiny German garrison at Lorengau were the last shots fired in the battle.
[src:caroline-islands/admiralty-islands] After the war, the islands were governed by the Commonwealth of Australia under a League of Nations mandate.
[src:caroline-islands/admiralty-islands] Japanese troops landed on Manus Island on 7 April 1942.
[src:caroline-islands/admiralty-islands] In 1944, Japanese forces occupying the islands were attacked and defeated by Allied forces in Operation Brewer.
[src:caroline-islands/admiralty-islands] Subsequently, a large American airbase and Manus Naval Base was built at Lombrum near Lorengau.
[src:caroline-islands/admiralty-islands] Following Papuan independence in 1975, the Admiralty Islands became part of Papua New Guinea.
[src:caroline-islands/admiralty-islands] They became the Manus Province of the Islands Region in Papua New Guinea.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] African-American history began in the 16th century, when mainly West African and Central African slave traders sold African artisans, farmers, and warriors to European slave traders, who transported them across the Atlantic to the Western Hemisphere.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] They were sold as slaves to European colonists and put to work on plantations, particularly in the southern colonies.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] A few were able to achieve freedom through manumission or escape, and founded independent communities before and during the American Revolution.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] After the United States was founded in 1783, most American Black people continued to be enslaved, primarily in the American South, with four million enslaved people only liberated after the Northern victory over the South in the Civil War of 1861 to 1865.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] During Reconstruction, African Americans gained citizenship and adult-males the right to vote; however, due to widespread belief in White supremacy, they were treated as second-class citizens and soon effectively disenfranchised in the South.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] These circumstances changed due to participation in the military conflicts of the United States, substantial migration out of the South, the elimination of legal racial segregation, and the civil rights movement which sought political and social freedom.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] However, racism against African Americans and racial socioeconomic disparity remain a problem into the 21st century.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] In the 20th and 21st centuries, immigration has played an increasingly significant role in the African-American community.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] Black population were immigrants, and 20% were either immigrants or the children of immigrants.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] While some Black immigrants or their children may also come to identify as African American, the majority of first-generation immigrants do not, preferring to identify with their nation of origin.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] Most African Americans are of West African and coastal Central African ancestry, with varying amounts of Western European and Native American ancestry (see §Genetics).
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] African-American culture has had a significant influence on worldwide culture, making numerous contributions to the English language, literature, politics, cuisine, sports, and music.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] The African-American contribution to popular music is so profound that most American popular music, including gospel, blues, jazz, rock and roll, R&B, soul, funk, disco, hip-hop, and house has its origins either partially or entirely in the African-American community.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] The vast majority of those who were enslaved and transported in the transatlantic slave trade were people from several Central and West African ethnic groups.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] They had been captured directly by European slave traders in coastal raids, or captured and sold by West African slave traders or by half-European "merchant princes" to European slave traders, who brought them to the Americas.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] The first African slaves in what is now the United States arrived in the early 16th century.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] Africans were among Juan Ponce de León's 1513 voyage that landed in what would become Spanish Florida, and enslaved Africans arrived around the same time to Spanish Puerto Rico.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] Africans also came via Santo Domingo in the Caribbean to the San Miguel de Gualdape colony (most likely located in the Winyah Bay area of present-day South Carolina), founded by Spanish explorer Lucas Vázquez de Ayllón in 1526.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] The ill-fated colony was almost immediately disrupted by a fight over leadership, during which the slaves revolted and fled the colony to seek refuge among local Native Americans.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] De Ayllón and many of the colonists died shortly afterward, due to an epidemic and the colony was abandoned.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] The settlers and the slaves who had not escaped returned to the Island of Hispaniola, whence they had come.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] The enslaved explorer Esteban arrived in Florida with the Narváez expedition in 1528, a journey that first landed in Santo Domingo and later traveled into Spanish Texas and the Southwest before ending in Mexico.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] The marriage between Luisa de Abrego, a free Black domestic servant from Seville, and Miguel Rodríguez, a White Segovian conquistador in 1565 in St.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] Augustine (Spanish Florida), is the first known and recorded Christian marriage anywhere in what is now the continental United States.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] The first recorded Africans in English America (including most of the future United States) were "20 and odd negroes" who arrived in Jamestown, Virginia via Cape Comfort in August 1619 as indentured servants.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] As many Virginian settlers began to die from harsh conditions, more and more Africans were brought to work as laborers.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] An indentured servant (who could be White or Black) would work for several years (usually four to seven) without wages.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] The status of indentured servants in early Virginia and Maryland was similar to slavery.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] Servants could be bought, sold, or leased, and they could be physically beaten for disobedience or attempting to running away.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] Unlike slaves, they were freed after their term of service expired or if their freedom was purchased.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] Their children did not inherit their status, and on their release from contract they received "a year's provision of corn, double apparel, tools necessary", and a small cash payment called "freedom dues".
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] Africans could legally raise crops and cattle to purchase their freedom.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] They raised families, married other Africans and sometimes intermarried with Native Americans or European settlers.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] By the 1640s and 1650s, several African families owned farms around Jamestown, and some became wealthy by colonial standards and purchased indentured servants of their own.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] In 1640, the Virginia General Court recorded the earliest documentation of lifetime slavery when they sentenced John Punch, a Negro, to lifetime servitude under his master Hugh Gwyn, for running away.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] In Spanish Florida, some Spanish married or had unions with Pensacola, Creek or African women, both enslaved and free, and their descendants created a mixed-race population of mestizos and mulattos.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] The Spanish encouraged slaves from the colony of Georgia to come to Florida as a refuge, promising freedom in exchange for conversion to Catholicism.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] King Charles II issued a royal proclamation freeing all slaves who fled to Spanish Florida and accepted conversion and baptism.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] Augustine, but escaped slaves also reached Pensacola.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] Augustine had mustered an all-Black militia unit defending Spanish Florida as early as 1683.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] One of the Dutch African arrivals, Anthony Johnson, would later own one of the first Black "slaves", John Casor, resulting from the court ruling of a civil case.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] The popular conception of a race-based slave system did not fully develop until the 18th century.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] The Dutch West India Company introduced slavery in 1625 with the importation of eleven Black slaves into New Amsterdam (present-day New York City).
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] All the colony's slaves, however, were freed upon its surrender to the English.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] Massachusetts was the first English colony to legally recognize slavery in 1641.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] In 1662, Virginia passed a law that children of enslaved women would take the status of the mother, rather than that of the father, as was the case under common law.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] This legal principle was called *partus sequitur ventrum*.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] By an act of 1699, Virginia ordered the deportation of all free Blacks, effectively defining all people of African descent who remained in the colony as slaves.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] In 1670, the colonial assembly passed a law prohibiting free and baptized Blacks (and Native Americans) from purchasing Christians (in this act meaning White Europeans) but allowing them to buy people "of their owne nation".
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] In Spanish Louisiana, although there was no movement toward abolition of the African slave trade, Spanish rule introduced a new law called *coartación*, which allowed slaves to buy their freedom, and that of others.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] Although some did not have the money to do so, government measures on slavery enabled the existence of many free Blacks.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] This caused problems to the Spaniards with the French creoles (French who had settled in New France) who had also populated Spanish Louisiana.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] The French creoles cited that measure as one of the system's worst elements.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] First established in South Carolina in 1704, groups of armed White men—slave patrols—were formed to monitor enslaved Black people.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] Their function was to police slaves, especially fugitives.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] Slave owners feared that slaves might organize revolts or slave rebellions, so state militias were formed to provide a military command structure and discipline within the slave patrols.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] These patrols were used to detect, encounter, and crush any organized slave meetings which might lead to revolts or rebellions.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] The earliest African American congregations and churches were organized before 1800 in both northern and southern cities following the Great Awakening.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] By 1775, Africans made up 20% of the population in the American colonies, which made them the second-largest ethnic group after English Americans.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] During the 1770s, Africans, both enslaved and free, helped rebellious American colonists secure their independence by defeating the British in the American Revolutionary War.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] Blacks played a role in both sides in the American Revolution.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] Activists in the Patriot cause included James Armistead, Prince Whipple, and Oliver Cromwell.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] Around 15,000 Black Loyalists left with the British after the war, most of them ending up as free Black people in England or its colonies, such as the Black Nova Scotians and the Sierra Leone Creole people.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] In the Spanish Louisiana, Governor Bernardo de Gálvez organized Spanish free Black men into two militia companies to defend New Orleans during the American Revolution.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] They fought in the 1779 battle in which Spain captured Baton Rouge from the British.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] Gálvez also commanded them in campaigns against the British outposts in Mobile, Alabama, and Pensacola, Florida.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] He recruited slaves for the militia by pledging to free anyone who was seriously wounded and promised to secure a low price for *coartación* (buy their freedom and that of others) for those who received lesser wounds.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] During the 1790s, Governor Francisco Luis Héctor, baron of Carondelet reinforced local fortifications and recruit even more free Black men for the militia.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] Carondelet doubled the number of free Black men who served, creating two more militia companies—one made up of Black members and the other of pardo (mixed race).
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] Serving in the militia brought free Black men one step closer to equality with Whites, allowing them, for example, the right to carry arms and boosting their earning power.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] However, actually these privileges distanced free Black men from enslaved Blacks and encouraged them to identify with Whites.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] Slavery had been tacitly enshrined in the US Constitution through provisions such as Article I, Section 2, Clause 3, commonly known as the 3/5 compromise.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] Due to the restrictions of Section 9, Clause 1, Congress was unable to pass an Act Prohibiting Importation of Slaves until 1807.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] Fugitive slave laws (derived from the Fugitive Slave Clause of the Constitution—Article IV, Section 2, Clause 3) were passed by Congress in both 1793 and 1850, guaranteeing the right of a slaveholder to recover an escaped slave anywhere within the US.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] Slave owners, who viewed enslaved people as property, ensured that it became a federal crime to aid or assist those who had fled slavery or to interfere with their capture.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] By that time, slavery, which almost exclusively targeted Black people, had become the most critical and contentious political issue in the Antebellum United States, repeatedly sparking crises and conflicts.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] Among these were the Missouri Compromise, the Compromise of 1850, the infamous Dred Scott decision, and John Brown's raid on Harpers Ferry.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] Prior to the Civil War, eight serving presidents had owned slaves, a practice that was legally protected under the US Constitution.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] By 1860, the number of enslaved Black people in the US had grown to between 3.5 and 4.4 million, largely as a result of the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] In addition, 488,000–500,000 Black people lived free around the country, with legislated limits imposed upon them in addition to "unconquerable prejudice" from Whites according to Henry Clay.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] In response to these conditions, some free Black people chose to leave the US and emigrate to Liberia in West Africa.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] Liberia had been established in 1821 as a settlement by the American Colonization Society (ACS), with many abolitionist members of the ACS believing Black Americans would have greater opportunities for freedom and equality in Africa than they would in the US.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] Slaves not only represented a significant financial investment for their owners, but they also played a crucial role in producing the country's most valuable product and export: cotton.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] Enslaved people were instrumental in the construction of several prominent structures such as, the United States Capitol, the White House and other Washington, D.C.–based buildings.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] Similar building projects existed in the slave states.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] By 1815, the domestic slave trade had become a significant and major economic activity in the United States, continuing to flourish until the 1860s.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] Historians estimate that nearly one million individuals were subjected to this forced migration, which was often referred to as a new "Middle Passage".
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] The historian Ira Berlin described this internal forced migration of enslaved people as the "central event" in the life of a slave during the period between the American Revolution and the Civil War.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] Berlin emphasized that whether enslaved individuals were directly uprooted or lived in constant fear that they or their families would be involuntarily relocated, "the massive deportation traumatized Black people" throughout the US.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] As a result of this large-scale forced movement, countless individuals lost their connection to families and clans, and many ethnic Africans lost their knowledge of varying tribal origins in Africa.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] Emigration of free Blacks to their continent of origin had been proposed since the Revolutionary war.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] After Haiti became independent, it tried to recruit African Americans to migrate there after it re-established trade relations with the United States.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] The Haitian Union was a group formed to promote relations between the countries.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] After riots against Blacks in Cincinnati, its Black community sponsored founding of the Wilberforce Colony, an initially successful settlement of African American immigrants to Canada.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] The colony was one of the first such independent political entities.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] It lasted for a number of decades and provided a destination for about 200 Black families emigrating from a number of locations in the United States.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] In 1863, during the American Civil War, President Abraham Lincoln signed the Emancipation Proclamation.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] The proclamation declared that all slaves in Confederate-held territory were free.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] Advancing Union troops enforced the proclamation, with Texas being the last state to be emancipated, in 1865.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] Slavery in a few border states continued until the ratification of the Thirteenth Amendment in December 1865.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] While the Naturalization Act of 1790 limited US citizenship to Whites only, the 14th Amendment (1868) gave Black people citizenship, and the 15th Amendment (1870) gave Black men the right to vote.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] African Americans quickly set up congregations for themselves, as well as schools and community/civic associations, to have space away from White control or oversight.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] While the post-war Reconstruction era was initially a time of progress for African Americans, that period ended in 1876.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] By the late 1890s, Southern states enacted Jim Crow laws to enforce racial segregation and disenfranchisement.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] Segregation was now imposed with Jim Crow laws, using signs used to show Blacks where they could legally walk, talk, drink, rest, or eat.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] For those places that were racially mixed, non-Whites had to wait until all White customers were dealt with.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] Most African Americans obeyed the Jim Crow laws, to avoid racially motivated violence.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] To maintain self-esteem and dignity, African Americans such as Anthony Overton and Mary McLeod Bethune continued to build their own schools, churches, banks, social clubs, and other businesses.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] In the last decade of the 19th century, racially discriminatory laws and racial violence aimed at African Americans began to mushroom in the United States, a period often referred to as the "nadir of American race relations".
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] These discriminatory acts included racial segregation—upheld by the United States Supreme Court decision in *Plessy v.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] The desperate conditions of African Americans in the South sparked the Great Migration during the first half of the 20th century which led to a growing African American community in Northern and Western United States.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] The rapid influx of Blacks disturbed the racial balance within Northern and Western cities, exacerbating hostility between both Blacks and Whites in the two regions.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] The Red Summer of 1919 was marked by hundreds of deaths and higher casualties across the US as a result of race riots that occurred in more than three dozen cities, such as the Chicago race riot of 1919 and the Omaha race riot of 1919.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] Overall, Blacks in Northern and Western cities experienced systemic discrimination in a plethora of aspects of life.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] Within employment, economic opportunities for Blacks were routed to the lowest-status and restrictive in potential mobility.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] While many Whites defended their space with violence, intimidation, or legal tactics toward African Americans, many other Whites migrated to more racially homogeneous suburban or exurban regions, a process known as White flight.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] Despite discrimination, drawing cards for leaving the hopelessness in the South were the growth of African American institutions and communities in Northern cities.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] Institutions included Black oriented organizations (e.g., Urban League, NAACP), churches, businesses, and newspapers, as well as successes in the development in African American intellectual culture, music, and popular culture (e.g., Harlem Renaissance, Chicago Black Renaissance).
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] The Cotton Club in Harlem was a Whites-only establishment, with Blacks (such as Duke Ellington) allowed to perform, but to a White audience.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] Black Americans also found a new ground for political power in Northern cities, without the enforced disabilities of Jim Crow.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] By the 1950s, the civil rights movement was gaining momentum.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] A 1955 lynching that sparked public outrage about injustice was that of Emmett Till, a 14-year-old boy from Chicago.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] Spending the summer with relatives in Money, Mississippi, Till was killed for allegedly having wolf-whistled at a White woman.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] Till had been badly beaten, one of his eyes was gouged out, and he was shot in the head.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] The visceral response to his mother's decision to have an open-casket funeral mobilized the Black community throughout the US.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] Vann Newkirk wrote "the trial of his killers became a pageant illuminating the tyranny of White supremacy".
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] The state of Mississippi tried two defendants, but they were speedily acquitted by an all-White jury.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] The March on Washington for Jobs and Freedom and the conditions which brought it into being are credited with putting pressure on presidents John F.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] By 1966, the emergence of the Black Power movement, which lasted from 1966 to 1975, expanded upon the aims of the civil rights movement to include economic and political self-sufficiency, and freedom from White authority.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] During the post-war period, many African Americans continued to be economically disadvantaged relative to other Americans.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] Average Black income stood at 54 percent of that of White workers in 1947, and 55 percent in 1962.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] In 1965, 43 percent of all Black families fell into the poverty bracket, earning under $3,000 (equivalent to $30,649 in 2025) a year.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] The 1960s saw improvements in the social and economic conditions of many Black Americans.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] From 1965 to 1969, Black family income rose from 54 to 60 percent of White family income.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] In 1968, 23 percent of Black families earned under $3,000 (equivalent to $27,775 in 2025) a year, compared with 41 percent in 1960.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] In 1965, 19 percent of Black Americans had incomes equal to the national median, a proportion that rose to 27 percent by 1967.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] In 1960, the median level of education for Blacks had been 10.8 years, and by the late 1960s, the figure rose to 12.2 years, half a year behind the median for Whites.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] Politically and economically, African Americans have made substantial strides during the post–civil rights era.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] In 1967, Thurgood Marshall became the first African American Supreme Court Justice.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] In 1968, Shirley Chisholm became the first Black woman elected to the US Congress.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] In 1989, Douglas Wilder became the first African American elected governor in US history.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] Clarence Thomas succeeded Marshall to become the second African American Supreme Court Justice in 1991.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] In 1992, Carol Moseley-Braun of Illinois became the first African American woman elected to the US Senate.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] There were 8,936 Black officeholders in the United States in 2000, showing a net increase of 7,467 since 1970.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] In 2005, the number of Africans immigrating to the United States, in a single year, surpassed the peak number who were involuntarily brought to the United States during the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] On November 4, 2008, Democratic Senator Barack Obama—the son of a White American mother and a Kenyan father—defeated Republican Senator John McCain to become the first African American to be elected president.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] At least 95 percent of African American voters voted for Obama.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] He also received overwhelming support from young and educated Whites, a majority of Asians, and Hispanics, picking up a number of new states in the Democratic electoral column.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] Obama lost the overall White vote, although he won a larger proportion of White votes than any previous non-incumbent Democratic presidential candidate since Jimmy Carter.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] Obama was reelected for a second and final term, by a similar margin on November 6, 2012.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] In 2021, Kamala Harris, the daughter of a Jamaican father and Indian mother, became the first woman, the first African American, and the first Asian American to serve as Vice President of the United States.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p01] In June 2021, Juneteenth, a day which commemorates the end of slavery in the US, became a federal holiday.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] In 1790, when the first US census was taken, Africans (including slaves and free people) numbered about 760,000—about 19.3% of the population.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] In 1860, at the start of the Civil War, the African American population had increased to 4.4 million, but the percentage rate dropped to 14% of the overall population of the country.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] The vast majority were slaves, with only 488,000 counted as "freemen".
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] By 1900, the Black population had doubled and reached 8.8 million.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] In 1910, about 90% of African Americans lived in the South.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Large numbers began migrating north looking for better job opportunities and living conditions, and to escape Jim Crow laws and racial violence.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] The Great Migration, as it was called, spanned the 1890s to the 1970s.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] From 1916 through the 1960s, more than six million Black people moved north.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] But in the 1970s and 1980s, that trend reversed, with more African Americans moving south to the Sun Belt than leaving it.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] By 1990, the African American population reached about 30 million and represented 12% of the US population, roughly the same proportion as in 1900.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] At the time of the 2000 US census, 54.8% of African Americans lived in the South.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] In that year, 17.6% of African Americans lived in the Northeast and 18.7% in the Midwest, while only 8.9% lived in the Western states.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] The west does have a sizable Black population in certain areas, however.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] California, the nation's most populous state, has the fifth-largest African American population, only behind New York, Texas, Georgia, and Florida.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] According to the 2000 census, approximately 2.05% of African Americans identified as Hispanic or Latino in origin, many of whom may be of Brazilian, Puerto Rican, Dominican, Cuban, Haitian, or other Latin American descent.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] The only self-reported *ancestral* groups larger than African Americans are the Irish and Germans.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] According to the 2010 census, nearly 3% of people who self-identified as Black had recent ancestors who immigrated from another country.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Self-reported non-Hispanic Black immigrants from the Caribbean, mostly from Jamaica and Haiti, represented 0.9% of the US population, at 2.6 million.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Self-reported Black immigrants from sub-Saharan Africa also represented 0.9%, at about 2.8 million.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Additionally, self-identified Black Hispanics represented 0.4% of the United States population, at about 1.2 million people, largely found within the Puerto Rican and Dominican communities.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Self-reported Black immigrants hailing from other countries in the Americas, such as Brazil and Canada, as well as several European countries, represented less than 0.1% of the population.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Mixed-race Hispanic and non-Hispanic Americans who identified as being part Black, represented 0.9% of the population.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Of the 12.6% of United States residents who identified as Black, around 10.3% were "native Black American" or ethnic African Americans, who are direct descendants of West/Central Africans brought to the US as slaves.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] These individuals make up well over 80% of all Blacks in the country.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] When including people of mixed-race origin, about 13.5% of the US population self-identified as Black or "mixed with Black".
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] However, according to the US Census Bureau, evidence from the 2000 census indicates that many African and Caribbean immigrant ethnic groups do not identify as "Black, African Am., or Negro".
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Instead, they wrote in their own respective ethnic groups in the "Some Other Race" write-in entry.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] As a result, the census bureau devised a new, separate "African American" ethnic group category in 2010 for ethnic African Americans.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Nigerian Americans and Ethiopian Americans were the most reported sub-Saharan African groups in the United States.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] In the 2020 census, the African American population was undercounted at an estimated rate of 3.3%, up from 2.1% in 2010.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Texas has the largest African American population by state with approximately four million.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Followed by Texas is Florida, with 3.8 million, and Georgia, with 3.6 million.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Mississippi is the state with the highest African American share of the population at 39%.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Followed by Mississippi is Louisiana at 34%, and Georgia at 32%.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] After 100 years of African Americans leaving the south in large numbers seeking better opportunities and treatment in the west and north, a movement known as the Great Migration, there is now a reverse trend, called the New Great Migration.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] As with the earlier Great Migration, the New Great Migration is primarily directed toward cities and large urban areas, such as Charlotte, Houston, Dallas, Fort Worth, Huntsville, Raleigh, Tampa, San Antonio, New Orleans, Memphis, Nashville, Jacksonville, and so forth.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] A growing percentage of African Americans from the west and north are migrating to the southern region of the US for economic and cultural reasons.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] In 2020, New York City, Chicago, and Los Angeles metropolitan areas had the highest decline in African Americans, while Atlanta, Dallas, and Houston had the highest increase respectively.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Despite recent declines, as of 2020, the New York City metropolitan area still has the largest African American metropolitan population in the United States and the only to have over three million African Americans.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Among cities of 100,000 or more, South Fulton, Georgia had the highest percentage of Black residents of any large US city in 2020, with 93%.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Claiborne County, Mississippi is the Blackest county in the U.S. at 87% Black in 2020.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Cook County, Illinois has the largest Black population in the U.S. with 1,185,601 Black residents in 2020.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] The nation's most affluent community with an African American majority resides in View Park–Windsor Hills, California, with an annual median household income of $159,618 and median home price of about $1.5 million in 2025.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Additionally, there is a significant affluent Black presence in the southern Chicago suburbs of Cook County, Illinois.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] In 2006, Queens County, New York was the only county with a population of 65,000 or more where African Americans had a higher median household income than White Americans.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Seatack, Virginia is currently the oldest African American community in the United States.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] It survives today with a vibrant and active civic community.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] During slavery, anti-literacy laws were enacted in the US that prohibited education for Black people.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Slave owners saw literacy as a threat to the institution of slavery.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] When slavery was finally abolished in 1865, public educational systems were expanding across the country.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] By 1870, around seventy-four institutions in the south provided a form of advanced education for African American students.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] By 1900, over a hundred programs at these schools provided training for Black professionals, including teachers.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Many of the students at Fisk University, including the young W.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Du Bois, taught school during the summers to support their studies.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] African Americans were very concerned to provide quality education for their children, but White supremacy limited their ability to participate in educational policymaking on the political level.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] State governments soon moved to undermine their citizenship by restricting their right to vote.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] By the late 1870s, Blacks were disenfranchised and segregated across the American South.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] White politicians in Mississippi and other states withheld financial resources and supplies from Black schools.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Nevertheless, the presence of Black teachers, and their engagement with their communities both inside and outside the classroom, ensured that Black students had access to education despite these external constraints.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] During World War II, demands for unity and racial tolerance on the home front provided an opening for the first Black history curriculum in the country.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] For example, during the early 1940s, Madeline Morgan, a Black teacher in the Chicago public schools, created a curriculum for students in grades one through eight highlighting the contributions of Black people to the history of the United States.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] At the close of the war, Chicago's Board of Education downgraded the curriculum's status from mandatory to optional.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Predominantly Black schools for kindergarten through twelfth grade students were common throughout the US before the 1970s.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] By 1972, however, desegregation efforts meant that only 25% of Black students were in schools with more than 90% non-White students.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] However, since then, a trend towards re-segregation affected communities across the country: by 2011, 2.9 million African American students were in such overwhelmingly minority schools, including 53% of Black students in school districts that were formerly under desegregation orders.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] As late as 1947, about one third of African Americans over 65 were considered to lack the literacy to read and write their own names.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] By 1969, illiteracy as it had been traditionally defined, had been largely eradicated among younger African Americans.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Between 1995 and 2009, freshmen college enrollment for African Americans increased by 73 percent and only 15 percent for Whites.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Black women are enrolled in college more than any other race and gender group, leading all with 9.7% enrolled according to the 2011 US census.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] The average high school graduation rate of Blacks in the United States has steadily increased to 71% in 2013.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Separating this statistic into component parts shows it varies greatly depending upon the state and the school district examined.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] 38% of Black males graduated in the state of New York but in Maine 97% graduated and exceeded the White male graduation rate by 11 percentage points.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] In much of the southeastern United States and some parts of the southwestern United States the graduation rate of White males was in fact below 70% such as in Florida where 62% of White males graduated from high school.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Examining specific school districts paints an even more complex picture.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] In the Detroit school district, the graduation rate of Black males was 20% but 7% for White males.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] In the New York City school district 28% of Black males graduate from high school compared to 57% of White males.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] In Newark County 76% of Black males graduated compared to 67% for White males.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Further academic improvement has occurred in 2015.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Roughly 23% of all Blacks have bachelor's degrees.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] In 1988, 21% of Whites had obtained a bachelor's degree versus 11% of Blacks.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] In 2015, 23% of Blacks had obtained a bachelor's degree versus 36% of Whites.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Foreign born Blacks, 9% of the Black population, made even greater strides.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] They exceed native born Blacks by 10 percentage points.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] College Board, which runs the official college-level advanced placement (AP) programs in American high schools, have has received criticism in recent years that its curricula have focused too much on Euro-centric history.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] In 2020, College Board reshaped some curricula among history-based courses to further reflect the African diaspora.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] In 2021, College Board announced it would be piloting an AP African American Studies course between 2022 and 2024.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] The course officially launched in August 2024.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] In June 2023, the Supreme Court ended race-based affirmative action at American colleges and universities.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] In response, many of the nation's most prominent historically black colleges and universities (HBCUs) have reported a significant surge in applications and enrollment.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Slightly more than 250,000 African American students in the high school graduating class of 2025 took the Scholastic Aptitude Test (SAT) making up 13% of test takers.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] African American students had an average score of 904 which is lower than the national average of 1,209.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Asian American students had the highest average with 1,229.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] According to a 2025 study, African Americans have the highest average student debt.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] African Americans with bachelor's degrees owe an average of $52,726 in student loans.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Nearly 70% of African Americans took out a loan to fund their undergraduate education.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] African American women, in particular, carry the highest average student debt in the nation.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Historically black colleges and universities (HBCUs), which were founded when segregated institutions of higher learning did not admit African Americans, continue to thrive and educate students of all races today.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] There are 107 HBCUs representing three percent of the nation's colleges and universities with the majority established in the Southeast.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] HBCUs have been largely responsible for establishing and expanding the African American middle-class by providing more career opportunities for African Americans.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] The economic disparity between the races in the US has marginally improved since the end of slavery.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] In 1863, two years prior to emancipation, Black people owned 0.5 percent of the national wealth, while in 2019 it is just over 1.5 percent.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Racial disparity in poverty rates has narrowed since the civil rights era, with the poverty rate among African Americans decreasing from 24.7% in 2004 to 18.8% in 2020, compared to 10.5% for all Americans.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Poverty is associated with higher rates of marital stress and dissolution, physical and mental health problems, disability, cognitive deficits, low educational attainment, and crime.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] African Americans have a long and diverse history of business ownership.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Although the first African American business is unknown, slaves captured from West Africa are believed to have established commercial enterprises as peddlers and skilled craftspeople as far back as the 17th century.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Washington became the most famous proponent of African American businesses.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] DuBois also commended business as a vehicle for African American advancement.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] In 2002, African American-owned businesses accounted for 1.2 million of the US's 23 million businesses.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] As of 2011, African American-owned businesses account for approximately two million US businesses.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Black-owned businesses experienced the largest growth in number of businesses among minorities from 2002 to 2011.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Twenty-five percent of Blacks had white-collar occupations (management, professional, and related fields) in 2000, compared with 33.6% of Americans overall.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] In 2001, over half of African American households of married couples earned $50,000 or more.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Although in the same year African Americans were over-represented among the nation's poor, this was directly related to the disproportionate percentage of African American families headed by single women; such families are collectively poorer, regardless of ethnicity.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] In 2006, the median earnings of African American men was more than Black and non-Black American women overall, and in all educational levels.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] At the same time, among American men, income disparities were significant; the median income of African American men was approximately 76 cents for every dollar of their European American counterparts, although the gap narrowed somewhat with a rise in educational level.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Overall, the median earnings of African American men were 72 cents for every dollar earned of their Asian American counterparts, and $1.17 for every dollar earned by Hispanic men.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] On the other hand, by 2006, among American women with post-secondary education, African American women have made significant advances; the median income of African American women was more than those of their Asian-, European- and Hispanic American counterparts with at least some college education.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] The US public sector is the single most important source of employment for African Americans.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] During 2008–2010, 21.2% of all Black workers were public employees, compared with 16.3% of non-Black workers.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Both before and after the onset of the Great Recession, African Americans were 30% more likely than other workers to be employed in the public sector.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] The public sector is also a critical source of decent-paying jobs for Black Americans.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] For both men and women, the median wage earned by Black employees is significantly higher in the public sector than in other industries.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] In 1999, the median income of African American families was $33,255 compared to $53,356 of European Americans.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] In times of economic hardship for the nation, African Americans suffer disproportionately from job loss and underemployment, with the Black underclass being hardest hit.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] The phrase "last hired and first fired" is reflected in the Bureau of Labor Statistics unemployment figures.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Nationwide, the October 2008 unemployment rate for African Americans was 11.1%, while the nationwide rate was 6.5%.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] In 2007, the average income for African Americans was approximately $34,000, compared to $55,000 for Whites.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] African Americans experience a higher rate of unemployment than the general population.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] The income gap between Black and White families is also significant.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] In 2005, employed Blacks earned 65% of the wages of Whites, down from 82% in 1975.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] *The New York Times* reported in 2006 that in Queens, New York, the median income among African American families exceeded that of White families, which the newspaper attributed to the growth in the number of two-parent Black families.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] It noted that Queens was the only county with more than 65,000 residents where that was true.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] In 2011, it was reported that 72% of Black babies were born to unwed mothers.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] The poverty rate among single-parent Black families was 39.5% in 2005, according to Walter E.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Williams, while it was 9.9% among married-couple Black families.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Among White families, the respective rates were 26.4% and 6% in poverty.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Collectively, African Americans are more involved in the American political process than other minority groups in the United States, indicated by the highest level of voter registration and participation in elections among these groups in 2004.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] African Americans also have the highest level of Congressional representation of any minority group in the US.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Homeownership in the US is the strongest indicator of financial stability and the primary asset most Americans use to generate wealth.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] African Americans continue to lag behind other racial groups in homeownership.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] In the first quarter of 2021, 45.1% of African Americans owned their homes, compared to 65.3% of all Americans.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] The African American homeownership rate has remained relatively flat since the 1970s despite an increase in anti-discrimination housing laws and protections.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] The African American homeownership rate peaked in 2004 at 49.7%.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] The average White high school drop-out still has a slightly better chance of owning a home than the average African American college graduate usually due to unfavorable debt-to-income ratios or credit scores among most African American college graduates.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Since 2000, fast-growing housing costs in most cities have made it even more difficult for the US African American homeownership rate to significantly grow and reach over 50% for the first time in history.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] From 2000 to 2022, the median home price in the US grew 160%, outpacing average annual household income growth in that same period, which only grew about 30%.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] South Carolina is the state with the most African American homeownership, with about 55% of African Americans owning their own homes.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Black people, who make up 12% of the total U.S. population, make up 32% of all people experiencing homelessness, according to the data.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Since the mid 20th century, a large majority of African Americans support the Democratic Party.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] In the 2024 Presidential election, 86% of African American voters supported Democrat Kamala Harris, while 13% supported Republican Donald Trump.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Although there is an African American lobby in foreign policy, it has not had the impact that African American organizations have had in domestic policy.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Many African Americans were excluded from electoral politics in the decades following the end of Reconstruction.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] The African American trend of voting for Democrats can be traced back to the 1930s during the Great Depression, when Franklin D.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Roosevelt's New Deal program provided economic relief to African Americans.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Roosevelt's New Deal coalition turned the Democratic Party into an organization of the working class and their liberal allies, regardless of region.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] The African American vote became even more solidly Democratic when Democratic presidents John F.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Johnson pushed for civil rights legislation during the 1960s.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] In 1960, nearly a third of African Americans voted for Republican Richard Nixon.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Conservatism has been growing among African Americans, particularly since the 2020 Presidential election.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] In the 2024 election, Trump secured a slightly larger share of the African American vote compared to his 2020 performance.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] "Lift Every Voice and Sing" is often referred to as the Black national anthem in the United States.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] In 1919, the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP) had dubbed it the "Negro national anthem" for its power in voicing a cry for liberation and affirmation for African-American people.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] The majority of African Americans are Protestant, many of whom follow the historically Black churches.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] The term Black church refers to churches which minister to predominantly African American congregations.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Black congregations were first established by freed slaves at the end of the 17th century, and later when slavery was abolished more African Americans were allowed to create a unique form of Christianity that was culturally influenced by African spiritual traditions.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] According to a 2007 survey, more than half of the African American population are part of the historically Black churches.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] The largest Protestant denomination among African Americans is the Baptists, distributed mainly in four denominations, the largest being the National Baptist Convention, USA and the National Baptist Convention of America.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] The second-largest is the Methodists, the largest organizations of which are the African Methodist Episcopal Church and the African Methodist Episcopal Zion Church.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Pentecostals are distributed among several different religious bodies, with the Church of God in Christ as the largest among them by far.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] About 16% of African American Christians are members of White Protestant communions; these denominations (which include the United Church of Christ) mostly have a 2–3% African American membership.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] There are also large numbers of Catholics, constituting 5% of the African American population.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Of the total number of Jehovah's Witnesses, 22% are Black.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Historically, between 15 and 30% of enslaved Africans brought to the Americas were Muslims, but most of these Africans were converted to Christianity during the era of American slavery.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Prominent members included activist Malcolm X and boxer Muhammad Ali.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Malcolm X is considered the first person to start the movement among African Americans towards mainstream Islam, after he left the Nation and made the pilgrimage to Mecca.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] In 1975, Warith Deen Mohammed, the son of Elijah Muhammad took control of the Nation after his father's death and guided the majority of its members to orthodox Islam.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] African American Muslims constitute 20% of the total US Muslim population, the majority are Sunni or orthodox Muslims, some of these identify under the community of W.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] The Nation of Islam led by Louis Farrakhan has a membership ranging from 20,000 to 50,000 members.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] There is also a small but growing group of African American Jews, making up less than 0.5% of African Americans or about 2% of the Jewish population in the United States.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] The majority of African-American Jews are Ashkenazi, while smaller numbers identify as Sephardi, Mizrahi, or other.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Many African-American Jews are affiliated with denominations such as the Reform, Conservative, Reconstructionist, or Orthodox branches of Judaism, but the majority identify as "Jews of no religion", commonly known as secular Jews.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] A significant number of people who identify themselves as "Black Jews" are affiliated with syncretic religious groups, largely the Black Hebrew Israelites, whose beliefs include the claim that African Americans are descended from the Biblical Israelites.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Jews of all races typically do not accept Black Hebrew Israelites as Jews, in part because they are usually not Jewish according to Jewish law, and in part because these groups are sometimes associated with antisemitism.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] African-American Jews have criticized the Black Hebrew Israelites, regarding the movement as primarily composed of Black non-Jews who have appropriated Black-Jewish identity.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] In the 2010s, confirmed atheists were less than one half of one percent, similar to numbers for Hispanics.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] In 2025, a Pew Research Center study found that, among Black Americans, Christian affiliation has declined in recent years.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] The share of Black adults identifying as Christian fell from 85% in 2007 to 79% in 2014 and 73% in 2021, mirroring a broader decline in Christianity in the United States.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] However, Black adults remain more likely than U.S. adults overall to identify as Christian (73% vs.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] By comparison, about half or fewer adults in other racial or ethnic groups report that religion is very important or that they pray daily, and even smaller shares attend services monthly.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Religiosity among Black Americans also varies by age.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] 39% of Black adults aged 65 and older describe themselves as very religious, compared with 21% of those under 30.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] This age pattern is similar to that observed among White and Hispanic Americans, although Black adults of all ages are more likely than other groups to describe themselves as very religious.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] According to a Gallup survey, 4.6% of Black or African Americans self-identified as LGBT in 2016, while the total portion of American adults in all ethnic groups identifying as LGBT was 4.1% in 2016.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] African American women are more likely than African American men to openly identify as LGBT.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] The life expectancy for Black men in 2008 was 70.8 years.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Life expectancy for Black women was 77.5 years in 2008.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] In 1900, when information on Black life expectancy started being collated, a Black man could expect to live to 32.5 years and a Black woman 33.5 years.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] In 1900, White men lived an average of 46.3 years and White women lived an average of 48.3 years.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] African American life expectancy at birth is persistently five to seven years lower than European Americans.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Black men have shorter lifespans than any other group in the US besides Native American men.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Black people have higher rates of obesity, diabetes, and hypertension than the US average.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] For adult Black men, the rate of obesity was 31.6% in 2010.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] For adult Black women, the rate of obesity was 41.2% in 2010.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] African Americans have higher rates of mortality than any other racial or ethnic group for eight of the top ten causes of death.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] In 2013, among men, Black men had the highest rate of getting cancer, followed by White, Hispanic, Asian/Pacific Islander (A/PI), and American Indian/Alaska Native (AI/AN) men.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Among women, White women had the highest rate of getting cancer, followed by Black, Hispanic, Asian/Pacific Islander, and American Indian/Alaska Native women.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] African Americans also have higher prevalence and incidence of Alzheimer's disease compared to the overall average.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Black women lead the nation in abortions.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] According to a 2022 report, Black women made up 40% of abortions despite making up 13% of the U.S. woman population.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] African Americans are more likely than White Americans to die due to health-related problems developed by alcoholism.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Alcohol abuse is the main contributor to the top three causes of death among African Americans.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] In December 2020, African Americans were less likely to be vaccinated against COVID-19 due to mistrust in the US medical system.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] From 2021 to 2022, there was an increase in African Americans who became vaccinated.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Still, in 2022, COVID-19 complications became the third leading cause of death for African Americans.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Violence is a major problem within the African American community.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] A report from the US Department of Justice states "In 2005, homicide victimization rates for Blacks were more than six times as high as the rates for Whites".
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] The report also found that "94% of Black victims were killed by Blacks." Of the nearly 20,000 recorded US homicides in 2022, African Americans made up the majority of offenders and victims despite making up less than 15% of the population.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] In 2024, all of the five most dangerous US cities have a significant Black population and highly concerning Black-on-Black violent crime rate.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Black males age 15–44 are the only race/sex category for which homicide is a top-five cause of death.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Black women are three times more likely to be killed by an intimate partner than White women.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Black children are more than three times as likely to die due to parental abuse and neglect than White children.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] According to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, African Americans have higher rates of sexually transmitted infections (STIs) compared to Whites, with five times the rates of syphilis and chlamydia, and 7.5 times the rate of gonorrhea.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] The disproportionately high incidence of HIV/AIDS among African Americans has been attributed to homophobic influences, lack of condom usage, and lack of proper healthcare.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] The prevalence of HIV/AIDS among Black men is seven times higher than the prevalence for White men, and Black men are more than nine times as likely to die from HIV/AIDS-related illness than White men.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] The prevalence of HIV/AIDS among Black women is 20 times higher than White women, and Black women are more than 15 times as likely to die from HIV/AIDS-related illness than White women.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] African Americans have several barriers for accessing mental health services.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Counseling has been frowned upon and distant in utility and proximity to many people in the African American community.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] In 2004, a qualitative research study explored the disconnect with African Americans and mental health.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] The study was conducted as a semi-structured discussion which allowed the focus group to express their opinions and life experiences.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] The results revealed a couple key variables that create barriers for many African American communities to seek mental health services such as the stigma, lack of four important necessities; trust, affordability, cultural understanding and impersonal services.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Historically, many African American communities did not seek counseling because religion was a part of the family values.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] African Americans who have a faith background are more likely to seek prayer as a coping mechanism for mental issues rather than seeking professional mental health services.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] In 2015 a study concluded, African Americans with high value in religion are less likely to utilize mental health services compared to those who have low value in religion.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] In the United States, counseling approaches are based on the experience of White Americans and do not fit within the African American culture.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] African American families tend to resolve concerns within the family, and it is viewed by the family as a strength.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] On the other hand, when African Americans seek counseling, they face a social backlash and are criticized.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] They may be labeled "crazy", viewed as weak, and their pride is diminished.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Because of this, many African Americans instead seek mentorship within communities they trust.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Terminology is another barrier in relation to African Americans and mental health.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] There is more stigma on the term *psychotherapy* versus counseling.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] In one study, psychotherapy is associated with mental illness whereas counseling approaches problem-solving, guidance and help.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] More African Americans seek assistance when it is called counseling and not psychotherapy because it is more welcoming within the culture and community.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Counselors are encouraged to be aware of such barriers for the well-being of African American clients.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] Without cultural competency training in health care, many African Americans go unheard and misunderstood.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] In 2021, African Americans had the third highest suicide rate trailing American Indians/Alaska Natives and White Americans.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] However, African Americans had the second highest increase of its suicide rate from 2011 to 2021, growing 58%.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p02] As of 2024, suicide is the second leading cause of death among African-Americans between the ages of 15 and 24, with Black men being four times more likely to kill themselves than Black women.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Recent studies of African Americans using genetic testing have found ancestry to vary by region and sex of ancestors.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] These studies found that on average, African Americans have 73.2–82.1% Sub-Saharan African, 16.7–24% European, and 0.8–1.2% Native American genetic ancestry, with large variation between individuals.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Commercial testing services have reported similar variation, with ranges from 0.6 to 2 percent Native American, 19 to 29 percent European, and 65 to 80 percent Sub-Saharan African ancestry.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] According to a genome-wide study by Bryc et al.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] (2009), the mixed ancestry of African Americans in varying ratios came about as the result of sexual contact between West/Central Africans (more frequently females) and Europeans (more frequently males).
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] This can be understood as being the result of enslaved African American females being raped by White males.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Consequently, the 365 African Americans in their sample have a genome-wide average of 78.1% West African ancestry and 18.5% European ancestry, with large variation among individuals (ranging from 99% to 1% West African ancestry).
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] The West African ancestral component in African Americans is most similar to that in present-day speakers from the non-Bantu branches of the Niger-Congo family.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] (2014) observed that around 50% of the overall ancestry of African Americans traces comes from a population similar to the Niger-Congo-speaking Yoruba of southern Nigeria and southern Benin, reflecting the centrality of this West African region in the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] The next most frequent ancestral component found among African Americans was derived from Great Britain, in keeping with historical records.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] It constitutes a little over 10% of their overall ancestry and is most similar to the Northwest European ancestral component also carried by Barbadians.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] (2009) found a similar proportion of Yoruba-like ancestry in their African American samples, with a minority also drawn from Mandenka and Bantu populations.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Additionally, the researchers observed an average European ancestry of 21.9%, again with significant variation between individuals.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] (2009) note that populations from other parts of the continent may also constitute adequate proxies for the ancestors of some African American individuals; namely, ancestral populations from Guinea Bissau, Senegal and Sierra Leone in West Africa and Angola in Southern Africa.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] An individual African American person can have over fifteen African ethnic groups in their genetic makeup alone due to the slave trade covering such vast areas.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Altogether, genetic studies suggest that African Americans are a genetically diverse people.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] According to DNA analysis led in 2006 by Penn State geneticist Mark D.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] According to Shriver, around five percent of African Americans also have at least 12.5% Native American ancestry (equivalent to one Native American great-grandparent and their forebears).
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Research suggests that Native American ancestry among people who identify as African American is a result of relationships that occurred soon after slave ships arrived in the American colonies, and European ancestry is of more recent origin, often from the decades before the Civil War.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Africans bearing the E-V38 (E1b1a) likely traversed across the Sahara, from east to west, approximately 19,000 years ago.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] E-M2 (E1b1a1) likely originated in West Africa or Central Africa.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] According to a Y-DNA study by Sims et al.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] (2007), the majority (≈60%) of African Americans belong to various subclades of the E-M2 (E1b1a1, formerly E3a) paternal haplogroup.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] This is the most common genetic paternal lineage found today among West/Central African males and is also a signature of the historical Bantu migrations.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] The next most frequent Y-DNA haplogroup observed among African Americans is the R1b clade, which around 15% of African Americans carry.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] This lineage is most common today among Northwestern European males.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] The remaining African Americans mainly belong to the paternal haplogroup I (≈7%), which is also frequent in Northwestern Europe.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] According to an mtDNA study by Salas et al.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] (2005), the maternal lineages of African Americans are most similar to haplogroups that are today especially common in West Africa (>55%), followed closely by West-Central Africa and Southwestern Africa (<41%).
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] The characteristic West African haplogroups L1b, L2b,c,d, and L3b,d and West-Central African haplogroups L1c and L3e in particular occur at high frequencies among African Americans.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] As with the paternal DNA of African Americans, contributions from other parts of the continent to their maternal gene pool are insignificant.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Formal political, economic and social discrimination against minorities has been present throughout American history.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Saito, Associate Professor of Sociology and American Studies & Ethnicity at the University of Southern California, writes, "Political rights have been circumscribed by race, class and gender since the founding of the United States, when the right to vote was restricted to White men of property.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Those who economically gained the most from slavery were the planter class, owners of large-scale plantations where large numbers of enslaved Africans were held captive and forced to produce crops to create wealth for a White elite.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Although they have gained a greater degree of social equality since the civil rights movement, African Americans have remained stagnant economically, which has hindered their ability to break into the middle class and beyond.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] As of 2020, the racial wealth gap between Whites and Blacks remains as large as it was in 1968, with the typical net worth of a White household equivalent to that of 11.5 Black households.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Despite this, African Americans have increased employment rates and gained representation in the highest levels of American government in the post–civil rights era.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] However, widespread racism remains an issue that continues to undermine the development of social status.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Economically, of all the racially Black ethnic groups on the globe, African Americans are the wealthiest and most successful, with one in every fifty African American families being millionaires.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] This equates in 2023 to approximately 1.79 million African American millionaires in the United States, which is more than the number of millionaires in any racially Black country, and many other countries, around the world.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] In the US, which has the largest per-capita prison population in the world, African Americans are overrepresented as the second-largest population of prison inmates (38%) in 2023, coming second to Whites, who made up 57% of the prison population.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] According to the National Registry of Exonerations, Blacks are roughly 7.5 times more likely to be wrongfully convicted of murder in the US than Whites.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] In 2012, the New York City Police Department detained people more than 500,000 times under the city's stop-and-frisk law.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Of the total detained, 55% were African-Americans, while Black people made up 20% of the city's population.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] African American males are more likely to be killed by police when compared to other races.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] This is one of the factors that led to the creation of the Black Lives Matter movement in 2013.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] According to *The Guardian*, "The specter of Karen persisted as Black Lives Matter protests and civil unrest spread around the country following Floyd's murder and reckonings with racism began to roil institutions, toppling careers as well as statues".
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] In the aftermath of the peak Black Lives Matter protests and widespread police reform efforts in the early 2020s, crime rates surged across the nation, especially in predominantly Black neighborhoods.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Many cities experienced near-record or record levels of violence and other criminal activity.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] As a result, numerous municipalities scaled back police reform initiatives and increased funding for law enforcement.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] After over 50 years, marriage rates for all Americans began to decline while divorce rates and out-of-wedlock births have climbed.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] These changes have been greatest among African Americans.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] After more than 70 years of racial parity Black marriage rates began to fall behind Whites.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Single-parent households have become most common, and according to US census figures released in January 2010, only 38% of Black children lived with both their parents.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] In 2021, statistics show that over 80% marriages in the African American ethnic group marry within their ethnic group.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Black children are overrepresented in the U.S. foster care system.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] In 2017, Black American children made up 14% of the children population but 22% of those in the foster care system.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Black American children are more than twice as likely to be placed in foster care than White American children.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] The first ever anti-miscegenation law was passed by the Maryland General Assembly in 1691, criminalizing interracial marriage.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] In a speech in Charleston, Illinois in 1858, Abraham Lincoln stated, "I am not, nor ever have been in favor of making voters or jurors of negroes, nor of qualifying them to hold office, nor to intermarry with white people".
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] By the late 1800s, 38 US states had anti-miscegenation statutes.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] By 1924, the ban on interracial marriage was still in force in 29 states.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] While interracial marriage had been legal in California since 1948, in 1957 actor Sammy Davis Jr. faced a backlash for his involvement with White actress Kim Novak.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Harry Cohn, the president of Columbia Pictures, with whom Novak was under contract, gave in to his concerns that a racist backlash against the relationship could hurt the studio.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Davis briefly married Black dancer Loray White in 1958 to protect himself from mob violence.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Inebriated at the wedding ceremony, Davis despairingly said to his best friend, Arthur Silber Jr., "Why won't they let me live my life?" The couple never lived together, and commenced divorce proceedings in September 1958.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] In 1967 the law was ruled unconstitutional (via the 14th Amendment adopted in 1868) by the US Supreme Court in *Loving v.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] In 2008, Democrats overwhelmingly voted 70% against California Proposition 8, African Americans voted 58% in favor of it while 42% voted against Proposition 8.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] On May 9, 2012, Barack Obama, the first Black president, became the first US president to support same-sex marriage.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Since Obama's endorsement there has been a rapid growth in support for same-sex marriage among African Americans.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] As of 2012, 59% of African Americans support same-sex marriage, which is higher than support among the national average (53%) and White Americans (50%).
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Polls in North Carolina, Pennsylvania, Missouri, Maryland, Ohio, Florida, and Nevada have also shown an increase in support for same sex marriage among African Americans.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] On November 6, 2012, Maryland, Maine, and Washington all voted for approve of same-sex marriage, along with Minnesota rejecting a constitutional amendment banning same-sex marriage.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Exit polls in Maryland show about 50% of African Americans voted for same-sex marriage, showing a vast evolution among African Americans on the issue and was crucial in helping pass same-sex marriage in Maryland.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Black Americans hold far more conservative opinions on abortion, extramarital sex, and raising children out of wedlock than Democrats as a whole.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] On financial issues, however, African Americans are in line with Democrats, generally supporting a more progressive tax structure to provide more government spending on social services.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] African Americans have fought in every war in the history of the United States.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] The gains made by African Americans in the civil rights movement and in the Black Power movement not only obtained certain rights for African Americans but changed American society in far-reaching and fundamentally important ways.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Prior to the 1950s, Black Americans in the South were subject to de jure discrimination, or Jim Crow laws.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] They were often the victims of extreme cruelty and violence, sometimes resulting in deaths: by the post World War II era, African Americans became increasingly discontented with their long-standing inequality.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] The civil rights movement marked an enormous change in American social, political, economic and civic life.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Over time, it has changed in fundamental ways the manner in which Blacks and Whites interact with and relate to one another.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Some activists and academics contend that American news media coverage of African American news, concerns, or dilemmas is inadequate, or that the news media present distorted images of African Americans.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Johnson founded Black Entertainment Television (BET), a network that targets young African Americans and urban audiences in the United States.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Over the years, the network has aired such programming as rap and R&B music videos, urban-oriented movies and television series, and some public affairs programs.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] On Sunday mornings, BET would broadcast Christian programming; the network would also broadcast non-affiliated Christian programs during the early morning hours daily.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] According to Viacom, BET is now a global network that reaches households in the United States, Caribbean, Canada, and the United Kingdom.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] The network has gone on to spawn several spin-off channels, including BET Her (originally launched as *BET on Jazz*).
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Another network targeting African Americans is TV One.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] TV One is owned by Urban One, founded and controlled by Catherine Hughes.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Urban One is one of the nation's largest radio broadcasting companies and the largest African American-owned radio broadcasting company in the United States.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] In June 2009, NBC News launched a new website named TheGrio.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] It is the first African American video news site that focuses on underrepresented stories in existing national news.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] From their earliest presence in North America, African Americans have significantly contributed literature, art, agricultural skills, cuisine, clothing styles, music, language, and social and technological innovation to American culture.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] The cultivation and use of many agricultural products in the United States, such as yams, peanuts, rice, okra, sorghum, grits, watermelon, indigo dyes, and cotton, can be traced to West African and African American influences.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Notable examples include George Washington Carver, who created nearly 500 products from peanuts, sweet potatoes, and pecans.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Soul food is a variety of cuisine popular among African Americans.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] It is closely related to the cuisine of the Southern United States.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] The descriptive terminology may have originated in the mid-1960s, when *soul* was a common definer used to describe African American culture (for example, soul music).
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] African Americans were the first peoples in the United States to make fried chicken, along with Scottish immigrants to the South.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Although the Scottish had been frying chicken before they emigrated, they lacked the spices and flavor that African Americans had used when preparing the meal.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] The Scottish American settlers therefore adopted the African American method of seasoning chicken.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] However, fried chicken was generally a rare meal in the African American community and was usually reserved for special events or celebrations.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] African-American English is a variety (dialect, ethnolect, and sociolect) of American English, commonly spoken by urban working-class and largely bi-dialectal middle-class African Americans.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] It shares parts of its grammar and phonology with the Southern American English dialect.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] African American English differs from Standard American English (SAE) in certain pronunciation characteristics, tense usage, and grammatical structures, which were derived from West African languages (particularly those belonging to the Niger–Congo family).
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Virtually all habitual speakers of African American English can understand and communicate in Standard American English.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] As with all linguistic forms, AAVE's usage is influenced by various factors, including geographical, educational and socioeconomic background, as well as formality of setting.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Additionally, there are many literary uses of this variety of English, particularly in African American literature.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Other languages are spoken by specific sub-communities.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] The Gullah language is an English-based creole language spoken mostly in the coastal regions of South Carolina and Georgia by the Gullah; an off-shoot of this is Afro-Seminole Creole spoken by Black Seminoles mostly now in Mexico and Brackettville, Texas.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Louisiana Creole is a French-based creole and spoken mostly in Louisiana.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] African-American names are part of the cultural traditions of African Americans, most of these cultural names having no connection to Africa but strictly an African American cultural practice that developed in the United States during enslavement.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] This new evidence became apparent by census records which show African Americans and White Americans, though they spoke the same language, chose to use different names even during times of enslavement, which is where and when the development of African American cultural names began.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Prior to this newer information, it was only thought that before the 1950s, and 1960s, most African-American names closely resembled those used within European-American culture.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Babies of that era were generally given a few common names, with children using nicknames to distinguish the various people with the same name.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] With the rise of 1960s civil rights movement, there was a dramatic increase in names of various origins.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] By the 1970s, and 1980s, it had become common among African Americans to invent new names for themselves, although many of these invented names took elements from popular existing names.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Prefixes such as La/Le, Da/De, Ra/Re and Ja/Je, and suffixes like -ique/iqua, -isha and -aun/-awn are common, as are inventive spellings for common names.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] The book *Baby Names Now: From Classic to Cool—The Very Last Word on First Names* places the origins of "La" names in African-American culture in New Orleans.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Even with the rise of inventive names, it is still common for African Americans to use biblical, historical, or traditional European names.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Daniel, Christopher, Michael, David, James, Joseph, and Matthew were thus among the most frequent names for African-American boys in 2013.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] The name LaKeisha is typically considered American in origin but has elements that were drawn from both French and West/Central African roots.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Names such as LaTanisha, JaMarcus, DeAndre, and Shaniqua were created in the same way.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Punctuation marks are seen more often within African American names than other American names, such as the names Mo'nique and D'Andre.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] African American music is one of the most pervasive African American cultural influences in the United States today and is among the most dominant in mainstream popular music.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Hip-hop, R&B, funk, rock and roll, soul, blues, and other contemporary American musical forms originated in Black communities and evolved from other Black forms of music, including blues, doo-wop, barbershop, ragtime, bluegrass, jazz, and gospel music.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] African American-derived musical forms have also influenced and been incorporated into virtually every other popular music genre in the world, including country and techno.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] African Americans have also had an important role in American dance.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Jones, a prominent modern choreographer and dancer, has included historical African American themes in his work, particularly in the piece "Last Supper at Uncle Tom's Cabin/The Promised Land".
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Likewise, Alvin Ailey's artistic work, including his "Revelations" based on his experience growing up as an African American in the South during the 1930s, has had a significant influence on modern dance.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Another form of dance, stepping, is an African American tradition whose performance and competition has been formalized through the traditionally Black fraternities and sororities at universities.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Discussions of race and sports in the United States, where the two subjects have always been intertwined in American history, have focused to a great extent on African Americans.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Depending on the type of sport and performance level, African Americans are reported to be over- or under-represented.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] African Americans compose the highest percentage of the minority groups active at the professional level, but are among those who show the lowest participation overall.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] And though the list of African Americans in professional sports remains high, it only represents a small fraction of aspiring black athletes.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Many African American authors have written stories, poems, and essays influenced by their experiences as African Americans.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] African American literature is a major genre in American literature.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Famous examples include Langston Hughes, James Baldwin, Richard Wright, Zora Neale Hurston, Ralph Ellison, Nobel Prize winner Toni Morrison, and Maya Angelou.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] African American inventors have created many widely used devices in the world and have contributed to international innovation.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Norbert Rillieux created the technique for converting sugar cane juice into white sugar crystals.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Moreover, Rillieux left Louisiana in 1854 and went to France, where he spent ten years working with the Champollions deciphering Egyptian hieroglyphics from the Rosetta Stone.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Most slave inventors were nameless, such as the slave owned by the Confederate President Jefferson Davis who designed the ship propeller used by the Confederate navy.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] By 1913, over 1,000 inventions were patented by Black Americans.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Among the most notable inventors were Jan Matzeliger, who developed the first machine to mass-produce shoes, and Elijah McCoy, who invented automatic lubrication devices for steam engines.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Granville Woods had 35 patents to improve electric railway systems, including the first system to allow moving trains to communicate.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Morgan developed the first automatic traffic signal and gas mask.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Lewis Howard Latimer invented an improvement for the incandescent light bulb.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] More recent inventors include Frederick McKinley Jones, who invented the movable refrigeration unit for food transport in trucks and trains.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Lloyd Quarterman worked with six other Black scientists on the creation of the atomic bomb (code named the Manhattan Project) and helped develop the first nuclear reactor.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] As part of the preservation of their culture, African Americans have continuously launched their own publications and publishing houses, such as Robert Sengstacke Abbott, founder of the Chicago Defender newspaper, and Carter G.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Woodson, the founder of Black History Month who spent over thirty years documenting and publishing African American history in journals and books.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] The Johnson Publishing Company, founded by John H.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Johnson in 1942, is a National Historic Landmark.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] The term *African American* was popularized by Jesse Jackson in the 1980s, although there are recorded uses from the 18th and 19th centuries, for example, in post-emancipation holidays and conferences.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Earlier terms also used to describe Americans of African ancestry referred more to skin color than to ancestry.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Other terms (such as *colored*, *person of color*, or *negro*) were included in the wording of various laws and legal decisions which some thought were being used as tools of White supremacy and oppression.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] A 16-page pamphlet entitled "A Sermon on the Capture of Lord Cornwallis" is notable for the attribution of its authorship to "An *African American*".
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Published in 1782, the book's use of this phrase predates any other yet identified by more than 50 years.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] In the 1980s, the term *African American* was advanced to give descendants of American slaves, and other American Blacks who lived through the slavery era, a heritage and a cultural base.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] The term was popularized in Black communities around the country via word of mouth and ultimately received mainstream use after Jesse Jackson's use in 1988.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Subsequently, major media outlets adopted it.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Surveys in the 1990s and the first decade of the 21st century showed that the majority of Black Americans had no preference for *African American* versus *Black American*, although they had a slight preference for the latter in personal settings and the former in more formal settings.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] By 2021, according to polling from Gallup, 58% of Black Americans expressed no preference for what their group should be called, with 17% each preferring *Black* and *African-American*.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] In 2023, the government released a new more detailed breakdown due to the rise in racially Black immigration into the US, listing African American as a compound termed ethnicity, distinguished from other racially Black ethnicities such as Nigerian, Jamaican etc.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] The term *African American* embraces pan-Africanism as earlier enunciated by prominent African thinkers such as Marcus Garvey, W.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] The term *Afro-Usonian*, and variations of such, are more rarely used.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] In preparation for the 2010 US census, a marketing and outreach plan called *2010 Census Integrated Communications Campaign Plan* (ICC) recognized and defined African Americans as Black people born in the United States.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] From the ICC perspective, African Americans are one of three groups of Black people in the United States: African Americans, Black Africans, and Afro-Caribbeans.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] The ICC plan was to reach the three groups by acknowledging that each group has its own sense of community that is based on geography and ethnicity.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] The best way to market the census process toward any of the three groups is to reach them through their own unique communication channels and not treat the entire Black population of the US as though they are all African Americans with a single ethnic and geographical background.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Historically, "race mixing" between Black and White people was taboo in the United States.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] So-called anti-miscegenation laws, barring Blacks and Whites from marrying or having sex, were established in colonial America as early as 1691, and endured in many Southern states until the Supreme Court ruled them unconstitutional in *Loving v.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] The taboo among American Whites surrounding White-Black relations is a historical consequence of the oppression and racial segregation of African Americans.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Harvard University historian Henry Louis Gates Jr. wrote in 2009 that "African Americans...are a racially mixed or mulatto people—deeply and overwhelmingly so".
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] After the Emancipation Proclamation, Chinese American men married African American women in high proportions to their total marriage numbers due to few Chinese American women being in the United States.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] African slaves and their descendants have also had a history of cultural exchange and intermarriage with Native Americans, although they did not necessarily retain social, cultural or linguistic ties to Native peoples.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] There are also increasing intermarriages and offspring between non-Hispanic Blacks and Hispanics of any race, especially between Puerto Ricans and African Americans.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Racially mixed marriages have become increasingly accepted in the United States since the civil rights movement.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] A Gallup poll conducted in 2013 found that 84% of Whites and 96% of Blacks approved of interracial marriage, and 87% overall.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Black men are more than twice as likely to date and marry interracially than Black women.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] At the end of World War II, some African American military men stationed in Asia and Europe impregnated local non-Black women, resulting in the birth of thousands of mixed-race children called "Brown Babies".
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Some of these families later immigrated to the United States.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] However, some mixed-race children, especially in Japan, were placed in orphanages due to social stigmas associated with half-Black fatherless children in the 1950s.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Author Debra Dickerson has argued that the term *Black* should refer strictly to the descendants of Africans who were brought to America as slaves, and not to the sons and daughters of Black immigrants who lack that ancestry.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Thus, under her definition, President Barack Obama, who is the son of a Kenyan, is not Black.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] "Lumping us all together", Dickerson wrote, "erases the significance of slavery and continuing racism while giving the appearance of progress." Similar comments have been made concerning Kamala Harris, the daughter of a Jamaican immigrant, who was elected vice president in 2020.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] The American Descendants of Slavery (ADOS) movement coalesces around this view, arguing that Black descendants of American slavery deserve a separate ethnic category that distinguishes them from other Black groups in the United States.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Their terminology has gained popularity in some circles, but others have criticized the movement for a perceived bias against (especially poor and Black) immigrants, and for its often inflammatory rhetoric.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Politicians such as Obama and Harris have received especially pointed criticism from the movement, as neither are ADOS and have spoken out at times against policies specific to them.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Most notably, Malcolm X and Kwame Ture expressed similar views that African Americans are Africans who "happen to be in America", and should not claim or identify as being American if they are fighting for Black (New Afrikan) liberation.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Historically, this is due to the enslavement of Africans during the transatlantic slave trade, ongoing anti-Black violence, and structural racism in countries like the United States.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Before the independence of the Thirteen Colonies until the abolition of slavery in 1865, an African American slave was commonly known as a *negro*.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] *Free negro* was the legal status in the territory of an African American person who was not enslaved.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] The term was used until the second quarter of the 20th century, when it was considered outmoded – although it was retained in the name of the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP) – and generally gave way again to the exclusive use of *negro*.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] By the 1940s, the term was commonly capitalized (*Negro*); but by the mid-1960s, it was considered disparaging.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] By the end of the 20th century, *negro* had come to be considered inappropriate and was rarely used and perceived as a pejorative.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] The term is rarely used by younger Black people, but remained in use by many older African Americans who had grown up with the term, particularly in the Southern US.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] The term remains in use in some contexts, such as the United Negro College Fund, an American philanthropic organization.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] There are many other deliberately insulting terms, many of which were in common use (e.g., *nigger*), but had become unacceptable in normal discourse before the end of the 20th century.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] One exception is the use, among the Black community, of the slur *nigger* rendered as *nigga*, representing the pronunciation of the word in African American English.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] This usage has been popularized by American rap and hip-hop music cultures and is used as part of an in-group lexicon and speech.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] It is not necessarily derogatory and, when used among Black people, the word is often used to mean "homie" or "friend".
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] Acceptance of intra-group usage of the word *nigga* is still debated, although it has established a foothold among younger generations.
[src:caroline-islands/african-americans-p03] The NAACP denounces the use of both *nigga* and *nigger*.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] The **Caroline Islands** (or **the Carolines**) are a widely scattered archipelago of tiny islands in the western Pacific Ocean, to the north of New Guinea.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] Politically, they are divided between the Federated States of Micronesia (FSM) in the central and eastern parts of the group, and Palau at the extreme western end.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] Historically, this area was also called ***Nuevas Filipinas*** or **New Philippines**, because they were part of the Spanish East Indies and were governed from Manila in the Philippines.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] The Carolines are scattered across a distance of approximately 3,540 kilometers (2,200 mi; 1,910 nmi), from the westernmost island, Tobi, in Palau, to the easternmost island, Kosrae, a state of the FSM.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] The group consists of about 500 small coral islands, east of the Philippines, in the Pacific Ocean.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] The distance from Yap (one of the larger Caroline islands) to Manila is 1,200 mi (1,900 km).
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] Most of the islands are made up of low, flat coral atolls, but there are some that rise high above sea level.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] Some of the individual islands which make up the Carolines include - Yap, Chuuk (Truk), Pohnpei, Kosrae, Babeldaob, Satawal, Kapingamarangi, Nukuoro, Faichuk, Namonuito, Hall Island, Nomoi Islands, Weno, Rumung, Maap, Kanifay, Ngulu, Nett, Pingelap, and Lelu.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] The indigenous inhabitants speak a variety of languages, including: the Micronesian languages of Pohnpeian, Chuukese, Carolinian, and Kosraean; the Western Malayo-Polynesian languages of Palauan and Chamorro; and the unclassified language Yapese (possibly one of the Admiralty Islands languages).
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] There are also a significant number of inhabitants who belong to non-indigenous ethnic groups and speak other languages, including Filipinos and Japanese.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] The lingua franca used for trade and commerce among islanders who do not speak the same language is English.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] The indigenous people of these islands live mainly on horticultural products, fish, many different varieties of bananas, and taro (either the "swamp" or the "purple" variety).
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] On some islands, housing is still built using local materials such as coconut-palm thatch.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] As a result of missionary work over the centuries, Christianity is the religion most commonly practiced in this region of Micronesia.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] Many of the indigenous people adhere to the traditional belief in a supreme being called "Yalafar" and an evil spirit called "Can." For the most part, however, they do not engage in traditional religious rites.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] The inhabitants of Yap are noted for possessing an unusual currency.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] Besides the ordinary shell money, there is a sort of stone coinage, consisting of huge calcite or limestone discs or wheels from 6 inches to 12 feet in diameter, and weighing up to nearly 5 tons.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] These are all quarried in the Pelew Islands, 200 miles to the south, and must have been brought by native vessels or on rafts; later they were transferred on European vessels.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] The stones, which are rather tokens than money, do not circulate, but are piled up round about the chief's treasure-house, and appear to be regarded as public property.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] Some may not have been seen for some years, but the transfer of wealth is facilitated by a common understanding that a stone has a new owner.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] The Micronesian navigator Mau Piailug (1932–2010) was originally from the Carolinian island of Satawal.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] He learned the traditional navigation techniques of the Weriyeng school, which had been preserved after other traditional techniques had been forgotten (due partly to the remoteness of the Carolinian Islands).
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] In the 1970s, Mau shared his knowledge with members of the Polynesian Voyaging Society.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] This led to a revival of the practices of traditional Polynesian navigation techniques, and provided anthropologists with a greater understanding of the history of the Polynesian and Micronesian peoples.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] In 1985, a study was published that examined the origin of the sidereal compass used in the Caroline Islands.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] Different islands in the Carolines have passed down different legends about the origins and early histories of their peoples.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] Legend has it that the Saudeleur dynasty ended when another foreigner, called Isokelekel, invaded the islands, overthrew the Saudeleurs, and instituted the more decentralized *nahnmwarki* (tribal chief) system (which was maintained even during the later Colonial period, and still exists today).
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] The first contact that European explorers had with the Caroline islands was in 1525, when a summer storm carried the Portuguese navigators Diogo da Rocha and Gomes de Sequeira eastward from the Moluccas (by way of Celebes).
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] They ended up reaching several of the Caroline islands and staying there for several months, until 20 January 1526.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] Soon after, on 22 August 1526, the Spanish explorers Toribio Alonso de Salazar and Diego de Saavedra arrived in the area and recorded sighting the Island of San Bartolomé (Taongui).
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] About 8 months later, on 1 January 1528, the explorer Álvaro de Saavedra Cerón claimed possession of the Ulithi Islands on behalf of the king of Spain.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] He named them the **Islands of the Kings** (Spanish: *Islas de los Reyes*; French: *Îles des Rois*) after his patron and the Three Wise Men honored in the approaching Catholic feast of Epiphany.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] Spanish explorers visited the archipelago again in 1542 (Matelotes Islands), 1543, and 1545.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] In 1565, the islands were briefly visited by the first governor-general of the Philippines, Miguel Lopez de Legazpi (in office from 1565 to 1572).
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] Europeans did not visit the island again until 1686, when Francisco de Lezcano arrived in Yap.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] He called the islands *Las Carolinas*, in honor of Charles II of Spain.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] A Spanish royal decree, issued on 19 October 1707, authorized Spanish missionaries to make several expeditions to the Caroline Islands.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] However, in 1731, one such missionary, Juan Antonio Cantova, was killed.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] As a result, Spain ceased relations with the Caroline Islands.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] When they resumed relations in 1787, their emphasis was on trade and commerce.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] In 1852, a Spanish colonel named Coello suggested to the Spanish government that effective Spanish occupation of the Caroline Islands would help the Spanish engage in trade and commerce with the Philippines, Australia, New Guinea, and the Americas.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] His suggestion was ignored at first, but, in 1885, a Spanish government representative called Butron signed an agreement with the tribal chiefs of Koror and Artingal establishing Spanish sovereignty over the Caroline Islands.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] At that point, Spain attempted to impose customs duties on commercial exchanges in the region.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] However, Spain's previous abandonment of the islands had allowed the establishment of German and British missions on the islands, and Germany and the United Kingdom disputed Spain's right to collect customs revenue.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] The European powers called on Pope Leo XIII to arbitrate this dispute.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] He decided that Spain would have these rights on the islands west of the 164th meridian east, and Germany would have these rights on the Marshall Islands.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] Germany governed the archipelago as the *Karolinen*, and administratively associated it with German New Guinea.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] The islands were a popular resort for whaling ships in the 19th century.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] The first such vessel known to have visited was the London whaler *Britannia*, which called at Ngatik in December 1793.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] Such vessels—from Britain, the United States, Australia and elsewhere—came for water, wood, and food and, sometimes, for men willing to serve as crewmen on the vessels.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] These ships stimulated commerce and were significant vectors for change (both good and ill).
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] The islands most commonly visited were Kosrae, Mokil, Ngatik, Pingelap and Pohnpei.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] Japan invaded and occupied the islands in 1914 during World War I, as part of their campaign to take and occupy German colonial possessions.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] They installed two naval squadrons as part of this occupation.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] The Western Carolines were controlled by the squadron commanded by Rear Admiral Matsumura Tatsuo (1868–1932); while the Eastern Carolines were controlled by Vice-Admiral Yamaya Tanin (1866–1940).
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] In 1920, after World War I, Japan received a League of Nations mandate to control the Caroline and Marshall Islands.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] During World War II, Japan operated a large base at Truk Lagoon which it used for expansion into the southeastern Pacific.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] In the latter years of that war, during the Japanese withdrawal to the Japanese home islands, the Allies effectively neutralized Truk in Operation Hailstone.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] After the war, the islands (together with the Marshall Islands) became trust territories of the United States.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] The Federated States of Micronesia gained independence in 1986, followed by Palau in 1994.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] Two Jesuits, Juan Antonio Cantova (also known as John Anthony Cantova) and Victor Walter, attempted missionary work there in 1731; the former was soon murdered and the latter obliged to flee.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] In 1767, the Jesuits were suppressed in the Spanish dominions, and for the next 120 years there was no trace of a missionary in the islands.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] After the 1886 dispute between Germany and Spain over possession of the Carolines was settled by Pope Leo XIII in favor of Spain, the king of Spain directed Spanish Capuchins to go to the islands.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] The royal order was issued on 15 March 1886, and the *Propaganda Fide* officially established that mission on 15 May 1886, dividing it into two sections, named the West Caroline's and the East Carolines.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] Until that time, the islands had belonged ecclesiastically to the Vicariate Apostolic of Micronesia.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] The Spanish Capuchins caused a catechism and prayer book to be printed in the Ponape language, and Father Anthony of Valentia wrote a small grammar and dictionary of the Yap language in 1890.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] In 1899, after the Spanish priests had laid the foundations of the mission, the islands passed by purchase into the hands of Germany.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] Spain had contributed more than $5,000 a year towards the mission, but Germany contributed no support.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] Spain had compelled the indigenous people to send their children to school; Germany allowed people to choose to send their children or not.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] As a result, many people stopped attending church and sending their children to school, and the mission's fortunes suffered.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] In response, the *Propaganda Fide* decided on 7 November 1904 to replace the Spanish Capuchins with German missionaries, and on 18 December 1905 to erect a single Apostolic prefecture in place of the two separate missions.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] The Very Reverend Father Venantius of Prechtal, Germany, was appointed first prefect Apostolic at that time.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] In 1906, 24 missionaries (12 Fathers and 12 Brothers) were working in 13 stations, and several Sisters of St.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] Francis left Luxembourg to take charge of the 10 primary schools, in which a total of 262 children were enrolled.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] The missionaries boasted 90 adult converts that year, and reported that there were 1900 Catholics, a few Protestants, and 11,600 inhabitants who had not converted to Christianity.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] On 1 July 1905, the United States sent a Jesuit from the Manila Observatory to the island of Yap to erect a meteorological station there, and appointed the Capuchin Father Callistus as its director.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] The station was able to identify that the East-Asiatic typhoons were originating in the Carolines.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] The station made weather observations twice a day, and sent advance notice of severe weather to Manila.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] During the period of German control, Germany issued postage stamps for the islands.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] Transportation within the islands is either by boat or air (if in close proximity of an airfield).
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] Air travel is mostly domestic as most facilities cannot handle large aircraft.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] Caroline Islands Air is a chartered and the only domestic airline.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] Palau and Yap are the only places outside the Philippines where *Callicarpa micrantha* is native.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] Three of the four species in the genus *Ponapea* are endemic to the Caroline Islands.
[src:caroline-islands/caroline-islands] The island of Kosrae has fifteen species of land snails endemic to the island.
